Commutative ring spectra

Birgit Richter Fachbereich Mathematik der Universit√§t Hamburg, Bundesstra√üe 55, 20146 Hamburg, Germany richter@math.uni-hamburg.de http://www.math.uni-hamburg.de/home/richter/
Abstract.

In this survey paper on commutative ring spectra we present some basic features of commutative ring spectra and discuss model category structures. As a first interesting class of examples of such ring spectra we focus on (commutative) algebra spectra over commutative Eilenberg-Mac‚ÄâLane ring spectra. We present two constructions that yield commutative ring spectra: Thom spectra associated to infinite loop maps and Segal‚Äôs construction starting with bipermutative categories. We define topological Hochschild homology, some of its variants, and topological Andr√©-Quillen homology. Obstruction theory for commutative structures on ring spectra is described in two versions. The notion of √©tale extensions in the spectral world is tricky and we explain why. We define Picard groups and Brauer groups of commutative ring spectra and present examples.

Key words and phrases:
Commutative ring spectra, E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-structures on ring spectra, obstruction theory, units of ring spectra, Thom spectra, topological Hochschild homology, topological Andr√©-Quillen homology, √©tale maps, descent
2000 Mathematics Subject Classification:
55P43, 55N35

1. Introduction

Since the 1990‚Äôs we have several symmetric monoidal categories of spectra at our disposal whose homotopy category is the stable homotopy category. The monoidal structure is usually denoted by ‚àß\wedge and is called the smash product of spectra. So since then we can talk about commutative objects in any of these categories ‚Äì these are commutative ring spectra. Even before such symmetric monoidal categories were constructed, the consequences of their existence were described. In [122, ¬ß2] Friedhelm Waldhausen outlines the role of ‚Äòrings up to homotopy‚Äô. He also coined the expression ‚Äòbrave new rings‚Äô in a 1988 talk at Northwestern.

So what is the problem? Why don‚Äôt we just write down nice commutative models of our favorite homotopy types and are down with it? Why does it make sense to have a whole chapter about this topic?

In algebra, if someone tells you to check whether a given ring is commutative, then you can sit down and check the axiom for commutativity and you should be fine. In stable homotopy theory the problem is more involved, since strict commutativity may only be satisfied by some preferred point set level model of the underlying associative ring spectrum and the operadic incarnation of commutativity is an extra structure rather than a condition.

There is one class of commutative ring spectra that is easy to construct. If you take singular cohomology with coefficients in a commutative ring RùëÖR, then this is represented by the Eilenberg-MacLane spectrum ùêªùëÖùêªùëÖ\mathit{HR} and this can be represented by a commutative ring spectrum.

So it would be nice if we could have explicit models for other homotopy types that come naturally equipped with a commutative ring structure. Sometimes this is possible. If you are interested in real (or complex) vector bundles over your space, then you want to understand real (or complex) topological K-theory and Michael Joachim [56] for instance produced an explicit analytically flavoured model for periodic real topological K-theory as a commutative ring spectrum in the setting of symmetric spectra [54].

There are a few general constructions that produce commutative ring spectra for you. For instance, the construction of Thom spectra often gives rise to commutative ring spectra. We will discuss this important class of examples in Section 4. A classical construction due to Graeme Segal also produces small nice models of commutative ring spectra (see Section 5).

Quite often, however, the spectra that we like are constructed in a synthetic way: You have some commutative ring spectrum RùëÖR and you kill a regular sequence of elements in its graded commutative ring of homotopy groups, (x1,x2,‚Ä¶)subscriptùë•1subscriptùë•2‚Ä¶(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots), xi‚ààœÄ‚àó‚Äã(R)subscriptùë•ùëñsubscriptùúãùëÖx_{i}\in\pi_{*}(R), and you consider a spectrum Eùê∏E with homotopy groups œÄ‚àó‚Äã(E)‚âÖœÄ‚àó‚Äã(R)/(x1,x2,‚Ä¶)subscriptùúãùê∏subscriptùúãùëÖsubscriptùë•1subscriptùë•2‚Ä¶\pi_{*}(E)\cong\pi_{*}(R)/(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots). Then it is not clear that Eùê∏E is a commutative ring spectrum.

A notorious example is the Brown-Peterson spectrum, ùêµùëÉùêµùëÉ\mathit{BP}. Take the complex cobordism spectrum ùëÄùëàùëÄùëà\mathit{MU}. Its homotopy groups are

œÄ‚àó‚Äã(ùëÄùëà)=‚Ñ§‚Äã[x1,x2,‚Ä¶]subscriptùúãùëÄùëà‚Ñ§subscriptùë•1subscriptùë•2‚Ä¶\pi_{*}(\mathit{MU})=\mathbb{Z}[x_{1},x_{2},\ldots]

with xisubscriptùë•ùëñx_{i} being a generator in degree 2‚Äãi2ùëñ2i. If you fix a large even degree, then you have a lot of possible elements in that degree, so you might wish to consider a spectrum with sparser homotopy groups. Using the theory of (commutative, 111-dimensional) formal group laws you can do that: If you consider a prime pùëùp, then there is a spectrum, called the Brown-Peterson spectrum, that corresponds to pùëùp-typical formal group laws. It can be realized as the image of an idempotent on ùëÄùëàùëÄùëà\mathit{MU} and has

œÄ‚àó‚Äã(ùêµùëÉ)‚âÖ‚Ñ§(p)‚Äã[v1,v2,‚Ä¶]subscriptùúãùêµùëÉsubscript‚Ñ§ùëùsubscriptùë£1subscriptùë£2‚Ä¶\pi_{*}(\mathit{BP})\cong\mathbb{Z}_{(p)}[v_{1},v_{2},\ldots]

but now the algebraic generators are spread out in an exponential manner: The degree of visubscriptùë£ùëñv_{i} is 2‚Äãpi‚àí22superscriptùëùùëñ22p^{i}-2. You can actually choose the visubscriptùë£ùëñv_{i} as the xpi‚àí1subscriptùë•superscriptùëùùëñ1x_{p^{i}-1}, so you can think of ùêµùëÉùêµùëÉ\mathit{BP} as a quotient of ùëÄùëàùëÄùëà\mathit{MU} in the above sense. Since its birth in 1966 [27] its multiplicative properties where an important issue. In [18] it was for instance shown that ùêµùëÉùêµùëÉ\mathit{BP} has some partial coherence for homotopy commutativity, but in 2017 Tyler Lawson finally shows that at the prime 222 at least, ùêµùëÉùêµùëÉ\mathit{BP} is not a commutative ring spectrum [61]!

There are even worse examples: If you take the sphere spectrum SùëÜS and you try to kill the non-regular element 2‚ààœÄ0‚Äã(S)2subscriptùúã0ùëÜ2\in\pi_{0}(S) then you get the mod-222-Moore spectrum. That isn‚Äôt even a ring spectrum up to homotopy. You can also kill all the generators vi‚ààœÄ‚àó‚Äã(B‚ÄãP)subscriptùë£ùëñsubscriptùúãùêµùëÉv_{i}\in\pi_{*}(BP) including p=v0ùëùsubscriptùë£0p=v_{0} and leaving only one vnsubscriptùë£ùëõv_{n} alive. The resulting spectrum is the connective version of Morava K-theory, k‚Äã(n)ùëòùëõk(n). At the prime 222 this isn‚Äôt even homotopy commutative. In fact, Urs W√ºrgler shows more [125]: If œÄ0subscriptùúã0\pi_{0} of a homotopy commutative ring spectrum has characteristic two, then it is a generalized Eilenberg-Mac‚ÄâLane spectrum. Recent work of Mathew, Naumann and Noel puts severe restrictions on finite E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring spectra [79].

So how do you decide such questions? How can you determine whether a given spectrum is a commutative ring spectrum if you don‚Äôt have a construction that tells you right away that it is commutative? This is where obstruction theory comes into the story.

There is an operadic notion of an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring spectrum that goes back to Boardman-Vogt and May. Comparison theorems [76], [111] then tell you whether these more complicated objects are equivalent to commutative ring spectra. In the categories of symmetric spectra, orthogonal spectra and SùëÜS-modules they are.

Obstruction theory might help you with a decision whether a spectrum carries a commutative monoid structure: One version [16] gives obstructions for lifting the ordinary Postnikov tower to a Postnikov tower that lives within the category of commutative ring spectra. The other kind finds some obstruction classes that tell you that you cannot extend some partial bits and pieces of a nice multiplication to a fully fledged structure of an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring spectrum or that some homology or homotopy operation that you observe contradicts such a structure. This can be used for a negative result (as in [61]) or for positive statements: There are result by Robinson [101] and Goerss-Hopkins [38, 39] that tell you that you have a (sometimes even unique) E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring structure on your spectrum if all the obstruction groups vanish. Most notably Goerss and Hopkins used obstruction theory to prove that the Morava stabilizer groups acts on the corresponding Lubin-Tate spectrum via E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-morphisms [38].

There are other things that are weird for commutative ring spectra. Quite often, we end up working with ideals in the graded commutative ring of homotopy groups, but as we saw above, this is not a suitable notion of ideal. There is a notion of an ideal in the context of (commutative) ring spectra [53] due to Jeff Smith, but still several algebraic constructions do not have an analogue in spectra.

The algebraic behaviour on the level of homotopy groups can be quite deceiving: complexification turns a real vector bundle into a complex vector bundle. This induces a map œÄ‚àó‚Äã(ùêæùëÇ)‚ÜíœÄ‚àó‚Äã(ùêæùëà)‚ÜísubscriptùúãùêæùëÇsubscriptùúãùêæùëà\pi_{*}(\mathit{KO})\rightarrow\pi_{*}(\mathit{KU}) which can be realized as a map of commutative ring spectra c:ùêæùëÇ‚Üíùêæùëà:ùëê‚ÜíùêæùëÇùêæùëàc\colon\mathit{KO}\rightarrow\mathit{KU}. On homotopy groups we get

(1.1) œÄ‚àó‚Äã(c):œÄ‚àó‚Äã(ùêæùëÇ)=‚Ñ§‚Äã[Œ∑,y,œâ¬±1]/(2‚ÄãŒ∑,Œ∑3,Œ∑‚Äãy,y2‚àí4‚Äãw)‚Üí‚Ñ§‚Äã[u¬±1]‚ÄãœÄ‚àó‚Äã(ùêæùëà).:subscriptùúãùëêsubscriptùúãùêæùëÇ‚Ñ§ùúÇùë¶superscriptùúîplus-or-minus12ùúÇsuperscriptùúÇ3ùúÇùë¶superscriptùë¶24ùë§‚Üí‚Ñ§delimited-[]superscriptùë¢plus-or-minus1subscriptùúãùêæùëà\pi_{*}(c)\colon\pi_{*}(\mathit{KO})=\mathbb{Z}[\eta,y,\omega^{\pm 1}]/(2\eta,\eta^{3},\eta y,y^{2}-4w)\rightarrow\mathbb{Z}[u^{\pm 1}]\pi_{*}(\mathit{KU}).

Here the degrees are |Œ∑|=1ùúÇ1|\eta|=1, |y|=4ùë¶4|y|=4, |w|=8ùë§8|w|=8, |u|=2ùë¢2|u|=2 and yùë¶y is sent to 2‚Äãu22superscriptùë¢22u^{2}. So on the algebraic level cùëêc is horrible. But John Rognes showed that the conjugation action on ùêæùëàùêæùëà\mathit{KU} turns the map c:ùêæùëÇ‚Üíùêæùëà:ùëê‚ÜíùêæùëÇùêæùëàc\colon\mathit{KO}\rightarrow\mathit{KU} into a C2subscriptùê∂2C_{2}-Galois extension of commutative ring spectra!

Even for ordinary rings, viewing a (commutative) ring RùëÖR as a (commutative) ring spectrum via the Eilenberg-Mac‚ÄâLane spectrum functor changes the situation completely. The ring RùëÖR has a characteristic map œá:‚Ñ§‚ÜíR:ùúí‚Üí‚Ñ§ùëÖ\chi\colon\mathbb{Z}\rightarrow R because the integers are the initial ring. As a ring spectrum, H‚Äã‚Ñ§ùêª‚Ñ§H\mathbb{Z} is far from being initial. The map H‚ÄãœáùêªùúíH\chi can be precomposed with the unit map of H‚Äã‚Ñ§ùêª‚Ñ§H\mathbb{Z}

and the sphere spectrum SùëÜS is the initial ring spectrum! Now there is a lot of space between the sphere and any ring. I will discuss two consequences that this has: There is actually algebraic geometry happening between the sphere spectrum and the prime field ùîΩpsubscriptùîΩùëù\mathbb{F}_{p}: There is a Galois extension of commutative ring spectra (see 8.1) A‚ÜíH‚ÄãùîΩp‚Üíùê¥ùêªsubscriptùîΩùëùA\rightarrow H\mathbb{F}_{p}!

Another feature is that there exist differential graded algebras A‚àósubscriptùê¥A_{*} and B‚àósubscriptùêµB_{*} that are not quasi-isomorphic, but whose associated algebra spectra over an Eilenberg-Mac‚ÄâLane spectrum [117] are equivalent as ring spectra [31]. Similar phenomena happen if you consider differential graded E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-algebras: There are non quasi-isomorphic ones whose associated commutative algebras over an Eilenberg-Mac‚ÄâLane spectrum [98] are equivalent as commutative ring spectra [21].

Content

The structure of this overview is as follows: We start with some basic features of commutative ring spectra and their model category structures in Section 2. The most basic way to relate classical algebra to brave new algebra is via the Eilenberg-Mac‚ÄâLane spectrum functor. We study chain algebras and algebras over Eilenberg-Mac‚ÄâLane ring spectra in Section 3. As you can study the group of units of a ring we consider units of ring spectra and Thom spectra in Section 4. In Section 5 we present a construction going back to Segal. Plugging in a bipermutative category yields a commutative ring spectrum.

In Section 6 we introduce topological Hochschild homology and some of its variants and topological Andr√©-Quillen homology. In Section 7 we discuss some versions of obstruction theory that tell you whether a given multiplicative cohomology theory can be represented by a strict commutative model.

Some concepts from algebra translate directly to spectra but some others don‚Äôt. We discuss the different concepts of √©tale maps for commutative algebra spectra in Section 8. Picard and Brauer groups for commutative ring spectra are important invariants and feature in Section 9.

Disclaimers

For more than 30 years, the phrase commutative ring spectrum meant a commutative monoid in the homotopy category of spectra. Since the 90‚Äôs this has changed. At the beginning of this new era people were careful not to use this name, in order to avoid confusion with the homotopy version. In this paper we reserve the phrase commutative ring spectrum for a commutative monoid in some symmetric monoidal category of spectra.

The second disclaimer is that for this paper a space is always compactly generated weak Hausdorff. I denote the corresponding category just by ùñ≥ùóàùóâùñ≥ùóàùóâ\mathsf{Top}.

Last but not least: Of course, this overview is not complete. I had to omit important aspects of the field due to space constraints. Most prominently probably is the omission of not discussing topological cyclic homology and its wonderful applications to algebraic K-theory.

I try to give adequate references, but often it was just not feasible to describe the whole development of a topic and much worse, I probably have forgotten to cite important contributions. If you read this and it affects you, then I can only apologize.

2. Features of commutative ring spectra

2.1. Some basics

Before we actually start with model structures, we state some basic facts about commutative ring spectra.

Let RùëÖR be a commutative ring spectrum. Then the category of RùëÖR-module spectra is closed symmetric monoidal: For two such RùëÖR-module spectra M,NùëÄùëÅM,N the smash product over RùëÖR, M‚àßRNsubscriptùëÖùëÄùëÅM\wedge_{R}N, is again an RùëÖR-module and the usual axioms of a symmetric monoidal category are satisfied. There is an RùëÖR-module spectrum FR‚Äã(M,N)subscriptùêπùëÖùëÄùëÅF_{R}(M,N), the function spectrum of RùëÖR-module maps from MùëÄM to NùëÅN.

We denote the category of RùëÖR-module spectra by ‚Ñ≥Rsubscript‚Ñ≥ùëÖ\mathcal{M}_{R}. The category of commutative RùëÖR-algebras is the category of commutative monoids in ‚Ñ≥Rsubscript‚Ñ≥ùëÖ\mathcal{M}_{R} and we denote this category by ùíûRsubscriptùíûùëÖ\mathcal{C}_{R}.

By definition, every object Aùê¥A of ùíûRsubscriptùíûùëÖ\mathcal{C}_{R} receives a unit map from RùëÖR and hence RùëÖR is initial in ùíûRsubscriptùíûùëÖ\mathcal{C}_{R}. In particular, the sphere spectrum is the initial commutative ring spectrum. Every discrete ring is a ‚Ñ§‚Ñ§\mathbb{Z}-algebra, similarly, every (commutative) ring spectrum is a (commutative) SùëÜS-algebra. If RùëÖR is a commutative ring spectrum, then the category of commutative RùëÖR-algebra is isomorphic to the category of commutative ring spectra under RùëÖR, i.e., such commutative ring spectra Aùê¥A with a distinguished map Œ∑:R‚ÜíA:ùúÇ‚ÜíùëÖùê¥\eta\colon R\rightarrow A in that category.

We allow the trivial RùëÖR-algebra corresponding to the one-point spectrum ‚àó‚àó\ast and this spectrum is a terminal object in ùíûRsubscriptùíûùëÖ\mathcal{C}_{R}.

In any symmetric monoidal category (ùíû,‚äó,1,œÑ)ùíûtensor-product1ùúè(\mathcal{C},\otimes,1,\tau) the coproduct of two commutative monoids Aùê¥A and BùêµB in ùíûùíû\mathcal{C} is A‚äóBtensor-productùê¥ùêµA\otimes B. So, for two commutative RùëÖR-algebras Aùê¥A and BùêµB, their coproduct is A‚àßRBsubscriptùëÖùê¥ùêµA\wedge_{R}B.

2.2. Model structures on commutative monoids

I will assume that you are familiar with the concept of model categories and that you have seen some examples and read Chapter 4 in this book. Good general reference are Hovey‚Äôs [52] or Hirschhorn‚Äôs [48] book. You could also just skip this section and have in mind that there are some serious model category issues lurking in the dark.

For this section I will mainly focus on two models for spectra: Symmetric spectra [54] and SùëÜS-modules [34]. They are different concerning their model structures. In the model structure in [54] on symmetric spectra the sphere spectrum is cofibrant whereas in the one for SùëÜS-modules it is not, but all objects are fibrant.

The model structures on commutative monoids in either of the categories [34, 54] are special cases of a right induced model structure: We have a functor PRsubscriptùëÉùëÖP_{R} from RùëÖR-module spectra to commutative RùëÖR-algebra spectra assigning the free commutative RùëÖR-algebra spectrum on MùëÄM to any RùëÖR-module spectrum MùëÄM, explicitly

PR‚Äã(M)=‚ãÅn‚©æ0M‚àßRn/Œ£n.subscriptùëÉùëÖùëÄsubscriptùëõ0superscriptùëÄsubscriptùëÖùëõsubscriptŒ£ùëõP_{R}(M)=\bigvee_{n\geqslant 0}M^{\wedge_{R}n}/\Sigma_{n}.

The symbol PRsubscriptùëÉùëÖP_{R} should remind you of a polynomial algebra. This functor has a right adjoint, the forgetful functor UùëàU. In a right-induced model structure one determines the fibrations and weak equivalences by the right adjoint functor. In our cases, a map of commutative RùëÖR-algebra spectra is a fibration or a weak equivalence, if it is one in the underlying category of RùëÖR-module spectra. Note that establishing right induced model structures on commutative monoids in some model category does not always work. The standard example is the category of ùîΩpsubscriptùîΩùëù\mathbb{F}_{p}-chain complexes (say pùëùp is an odd prime). Then the chain complex ùîª2superscriptùîª2\mathbb{D}^{2} is acyclic, having ùîΩpsubscriptùîΩùëù\mathbb{F}_{p} in degrees 111 and 222 with the identity map as differential, but the free graded commutative monoid generated by it is ŒõùîΩp‚Äã(x1)‚äóùîΩp‚Äã[x2]tensor-productsubscriptŒõsubscriptùîΩùëùsubscriptùë•1subscriptùîΩùëùdelimited-[]subscriptùë•2\Lambda_{\mathbb{F}_{p}}(x_{1})\otimes\mathbb{F}_{p}[x_{2}] with |xi|=isubscriptùë•ùëñùëñ|x_{i}|=i and the induced differential is determined by d‚Äã(x2)=x1ùëësubscriptùë•2subscriptùë•1d(x_{2})=x_{1} and the Leibniz rule. But then d‚Äã(x2p)ùëësuperscriptsubscriptùë•2ùëùd(x_{2}^{p}) is a cycle that is not a boundary, so the resulting object is not acyclic.

If RùëÖR is a commutative SùëÜS-algebra in the setting of EKMM [34], then the categories of associative RùëÖR-algebras and of commutative RùëÖR-algebras possess a right induced model structure [34, Corollary VII.4.10]. The existence of the model structure for commutative monoids is a special case of the existence of right-induced model structures for ùïãùïã\mathbb{T}-algebras ([34, Theorem VII.4.9]) where ùïãùïã\mathbb{T} is a continuous monad on the category of RùëÖR-module spectra that preserves reflexive coequalizers and satisfies the cofibration hypothesis [34, VII.4]. The category of commutative SùëÜS-algebras is identified [34, Proposition II.4.5] with the category of algebras for the monad PSsubscriptùëÉùëÜP_{S} as above on the category of SùëÜS-modules.

In diagram categories such as symmetric spectra and orthogonal spectra the situation is different: In the standard model structures on these categories the sphere spectrum is cofibrant. If one would take a right-induced model structure on the category of commutative monoids, i.e., the model structure such that a map of commutative ring spectra f:A‚ÜíB:ùëì‚Üíùê¥ùêµf\colon A\rightarrow B is a fibration or weak equivalence if it is one in the underlying category, then the sphere would still be cofibrant. If we take a fibrant replacement of the sphere S‚ÜíSfib‚ÜíùëÜsuperscriptùëÜfibS\rightarrow S^{\text{fib}}, then in particular SfibsuperscriptùëÜfibS^{\text{fib}} would be fibrant in the model category of symmetric spectra, hence it would be an Omega-spectrum and its zeroth level would be a strictly commutative model for Q‚ÄãS0ùëÑsuperscriptùëÜ0QS^{0}. However, Moore shows [90, Theorem 3.29] that this implied that Q‚ÄãS0ùëÑsuperscriptùëÜ0QS^{0} had the homotopy type of a product of Eilenberg-MacLane spaces ‚Äì but this is false.

The usual way to avoid this problem is to consider a positive model structure on S‚ÄãpŒ£ùëÜsuperscriptùëùŒ£Sp^{\Sigma} (see [76, Definition 6.1] for the general approach). Here the positive level fibrations (weak equivalences) are maps f‚ààS‚ÄãpŒ£‚Äã(X,Y)ùëìùëÜsuperscriptùëùŒ£ùëãùëåf\in Sp^{\Sigma}(X,Y) such that f‚Äã(n)ùëìùëõf(n) is a fibration (weak equivalence) for all levels n‚©æ1ùëõ1n\geqslant 1. The positive cofibrations are then cofibrations in S‚ÄãpŒ£ùëÜsuperscriptùëùŒ£Sp^{\Sigma} that are isomorphisms in level zero. The positive stable model category is then obtained by a Bousfield localization that forces the stable equivalences to be the weak equivalences and the right-induced model structure on the commutative monoids in S‚ÄãpŒ£ùëÜsuperscriptùëùŒ£Sp^{\Sigma} then has the desired properties.

There is another nice model for connective spectra, given by ŒìŒì\Gamma-spaces [114, 70]. This category is built out of functors from finite pointed sets to spaces, so it is a very hands-on category with explicit constructions. It is also a symmetric monoidal category with a suitable model structure. We refer to [70, 110] for background on this. Its (commutative) monoids are called (commutative) ŒìŒì\Gamma-rings. Beware that commutative ŒìŒì\Gamma-rings, however, do not model all connective commutative ring spectra. Tyler Lawson proves in [62] that commutative ŒìŒì\Gamma-rings satisfy a vanishing condition for Dyer-Lashof operations of positive degree on classes in their zeroth mod-pùëùp-homology (for all primes pùëùp) and that for instance the free E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring spectrum generated by ùïä0superscriptùïä0\mathbb{S}^{0} cannot be modelled as a commutative ŒìŒì\Gamma-ring.

2.3. Behaviour of the underlying modules

In the setting of EKMM it is shown that the underlying RùëÖR-modules of cofibrant commutative RùëÖR-algebras have a well-behaved smash product in the derived category of RùëÖR-modules:

Theorem 2.1.

[34, Theorem VII.6.7] ‚Äâ If Aùê¥A and BùêµB are two cofibrant commutative RùëÖR-algebras, and if and are chosen cell RùëÖR-module spectra approximations then

œÜA‚àßRœÜB:Œì‚ÄãA‚àßRŒì‚ÄãB‚ÜíA‚àßRB:subscriptùëÖsubscriptùúëùê¥subscriptùúëùêµ‚ÜísubscriptùëÖŒìùê¥ŒìùêµsubscriptùëÖùê¥ùêµ\varphi_{A}\wedge_{R}\varphi_{B}\colon\Gamma A\wedge_{R}\Gamma B\rightarrow A\wedge_{R}B

is a weak equivalence.

Brooke Shipley developed a model structure for commutative symmetric ring spectra in [116] in which the underlying symmetric spectrum of a cofibrant commutative ring spectrum is also cofibrant as a symmetric spectrum [116, Corollary 4.3].

She starts with introducing a different model structure on symmetric spectra. Let MùëÄM denote the class of monomorphisms of symmetric sequences in pointed simplicial sets and let S‚äóMtensor-productùëÜùëÄS\otimes M denote the set {S‚äóf,f‚ààM}tensor-productùëÜùëìùëìùëÄ\{S\otimes f,f\in M\} where ‚äótensor-product\otimes denotes the tensor product of symmetric sequences. An SùëÜS-cofibration is a morphism in (S‚äóM)tensor-productùëÜùëÄ(S\otimes M)-cof, i.e., a morphism in S‚ÄãpŒ£ùëÜsuperscriptùëùŒ£Sp^{\Sigma} that has the left lifting property with respect to maps that have the right lifting property with respect to S‚äóMtensor-productùëÜùëÄS\otimes M. She shows that the classes of SùëÜS-cofibrations and stable equivalences determine a model structure with the SùëÜS-fibrations being the class of morphisms with the right lifting property with respect to SùëÜS-cofibrations that are also stable equivalences [116, Theorem 2.4]. This model structure was already mentioned in [54, 5.3.6]. Shipley proves that this model structure is cofibrantly generated, is monoidal and satisfies the monoid axiom [116, 2.4, 2.5].

Note that symmetric spectra are SùëÜS-modules in symmetric sequences. This allows for a version of an RùëÖR-model structure for every associative symmetric ring spectrum RùëÖR with RùëÖR-cofibrations, RùëÖR-fibrations and stable equivalences [116, Theorem 2.6]. In the positive variant of this model structure the positive RùëÖR-cofibrations are RùëÖR-cofibrations that are isomorphisms in level zero. Together with the stable equivalences this determines the positive RùëÖR-model structure.

The corresponding right induced model structure on commutative RùëÖR-algebra spectra for a commutative symmetric ring spectrum RùëÖR is then the convenient model structure: The weak equivalences are stable equivalences, the fibrations are positive RùëÖR-fibrations and the cofibrations are determined by the structure.

She then shows the remarkable property of this model structure on commutative RùëÖR-algebra spectra:

Theorem 2.2.

[116, Corollary 4.3] ‚Äâ If Aùê¥A is cofibrant as a commutative RùëÖR-algebra then Aùê¥A is RùëÖR-cofibrant in the RùëÖR-model structure. If Aùê¥A is fibrant as a commutative RùëÖR-algebra, then Aùê¥A is fibrant in the positive RùëÖR-model structure on RùëÖR-module spectra.

The positive RùëÖR-model structure ensures that RùëÖR is not cofibrant, hence cofibrant commutative RùëÖR-algebras will not be positively RùëÖR-cofibrant!

2.4. Comparison, rigidification and Ensubscriptùê∏ùëõE_{n}-structures

Stefan Schwede proves [111, Theorem 5.1] that the homotopy category of commutative SùëÜS-algebras from [34] is equivalent to the homotopy category of commutative symmetric ring spectra by establishing a Quillen equivalence between the corresponding model categories. In [76, Theorem 0.7] the analogous comparison result is proven for commutative orthogonal ring spectra and commutative symmetric ring spectra.

Even before any symmetric monoidal category of spectra was constructed, the notion of operadically defined E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring spectra [81] was available. An E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-structure on a spectrum is a multiplication that is homotopy commutative in a coherent way. See Chapter 5 of this book for background on operads and their role in the study of spectra with additional structure.

There is an explicit comparison of the good old E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring spectra and commutative ring spectra, see [34, Proposition II.4.5] or [76, Remark 0.14], in particular, every E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring spectrum R~~ùëÖ\tilde{R} can be rigidified to a commutative ring spectrum RùëÖR in such a way that the homotopy type is preserved.

There are several popular E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-operads that will show up later: for instance the linear isometries operad (see (4.3)) and the Barratt-Eccles operad. The nùëõn-ary part of the latter is easy to describe: You take ùí™‚Äã(n)=E‚ÄãŒ£nùí™ùëõùê∏subscriptŒ£ùëõ\mathcal{O}(n)=E\Sigma_{n}, a contractible space with free Œ£nsubscriptŒ£ùëõ\Sigma_{n}-action. For compatiblity reasons it is advisible to take the realization of the standard simplicial model of E‚ÄãŒ£nùê∏subscriptŒ£ùëõE\Sigma_{n} whose set of qùëûq-simplices is (Œ£n)q+1superscriptsubscriptŒ£ùëõùëû1(\Sigma_{n})^{q+1}.

An operad with a nice geometric description is the little mùëöm-cubes operad, that in arity nùëõn consists of the space of nùëõn-tuples of linearly embedded mùëöm-cubes in the standard mùëöm-cube with disjoint interiors and with axes parallel to that of the ambient cube. [23, Example 5]. We call this (and every equivalent) operad in spaces Emsubscriptùê∏ùëöE_{m}. For m=1ùëö1m=1 this operad parametrizes A‚àûsubscriptùê¥A_{\infty}-structures and the colimit is an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-operad. Hence the intermediate Emsubscriptùê∏ùëöE_{m}‚Äôs for 1<m<‚àû1ùëö1<m<\infty interpolate between these structures, they give A‚àûsubscriptùê¥A_{\infty}-structures with homotopy-commutative multiplications that are coherent up to some order.

3. Chain algebras and algebras over Eilenberg-Mac‚ÄâLane spectra

The derived category of a ring is an important object in many subjects. The initial ring is the ring of integers. Every ring RùëÖR has an associated Eilenberg-Mac‚ÄâLane spectrum, ùêªùëÖùêªùëÖ\mathit{HR}.

3.1. ùêªùëÖùêªùëÖ\mathit{HR}-module and algebra spectra

We collect some results that compare the category of chain complexes of RùëÖR-modules with the category of module spectra over ùêªùëÖùêªùëÖ\mathit{HR}. We start with additive statements and move to comparison results for flavors of differential graded RùëÖR-algebras. For an overview of algebraic applications of these equivalences see for instance [41].

In the eighties, so before any strict symmetric monoidal category of spectra was constructed, Alan Robinson developed the notion of the derived category, ùíü‚Äã(E)ùíüùê∏\mathcal{D}(E), of right Eùê∏E-module spectra for every A‚àûsubscriptùê¥A_{\infty}-ring spectrum Eùê∏E. He showed the following result.

Theorem 3.1.

[99, Theorem 3.1] ‚Äâ For every associative ring RùëÖR there is an equivalence of categories between the derived category of RùëÖR, ùíü‚Äã(R)ùíüùëÖ\mathcal{D}(R), and the derived category of the associated Eilenberg-Mac‚ÄâLane spectrum, ùíü‚Äã(ùêªùëÖ)ùíüùêªùëÖ\mathcal{D}(\mathit{HR}).

Later, in the context of SùëÜS-modules this corresponds to [34, IV, Theorem 2.4]. Work of Schwede and Shipley strengthened the result to a Quillen equivalence of the corresponding model categories:

Theorem 3.2.

[113, Theorem 5.1.6] ‚Äâ The model category of unbounded chain complexes of RùëÖR-modules is Quillen equivalent to the model category of ùêªùëÖùêªùëÖ\mathit{HR}-module spectra.

Stefan Schwede uses the setting of ŒìŒì\Gamma-spaces [110] to embed simplicial rings and modules into the stable world: He constructs a lax symmetric monoidal Eilenberg-Mac‚ÄâLane functor HùêªH from simplicial abelian groups to ŒìŒì\Gamma-spaces together with a linearization functor LùêøL in the opposite direction and proves the following comparison result:

Theorem 3.3.

[110, Theorems 4.4, 4.5] ‚Äâ If RùëÖR is a simplicial ring, then the adjoint functors HùêªH and LùêøL constitute a Quillen equivalence between the categories of simplicial RùëÖR-modules and ùêªùëÖùêªùëÖ\mathit{HR}-module spectra. If RùëÖR is in addition commutative, then HùêªH and LùêøL induce a Quillen equivalence between the categories of simplicial RùëÖR-algebras and ùêªùëÖùêªùëÖ\mathit{HR}-algebra spectra.

Here, the functor LùêøL is actually left inverse to HùêªH and induces an isomorphism of ŒìŒì\Gamma-spaces

ùñßùóàùóÜ‚Äã(H‚ÄãA,H‚ÄãB)‚âÖH‚Äã(ùñßùóàùóÜùóåùñ†ùñª‚Äã(A,B))ùñßùóàùóÜùêªùê¥ùêªùêµùêªsubscriptùñßùóàùóÜùóåùñ†ùñªùê¥ùêµ\mathsf{Hom}(HA,HB)\cong H(\mathsf{Hom}_{\mathsf{sAb}}(A,B))

[110, Lemma 2.1], thus HùêªH embeds algebra into brave new algebra.

Brooke Shipley extends this equivalence to corresponding categories of monoids in the differential graded setting:

Theorem 3.4.

[117, Theorem 1.1] ‚Äâ For any commutative ring RùëÖR, the model categories of unbounded differential graded RùëÖR-algebras and ùêªùëÖùêªùëÖ\mathit{HR}-algebra spectra are Quillen equivalent.

Dugger and Shipley show in [31] that there are examples of ùêªùëÖùêªùëÖ\mathit{HR}-algebras that are weakly equivalent as SùëÜS-algebras, but that are not quasi-isomorphic. A concrete example is the differential graded ring A‚àósubscriptùê¥A_{*} which is generated by an element in degree 111, e1subscriptùëí1e_{1}, and has d‚Äã(e1)=2ùëësubscriptùëí12d(e_{1})=2 and satisfies e14=0superscriptsubscriptùëí140e_{1}^{4}=0. The corresponding H‚Äã‚Ñ§ùêª‚Ñ§\mathit{H}\!\mathbb{Z}-algebra spectrum is equivalent as a ring spectrum to the one on the exterior algebra B‚àó=ŒõùîΩ2‚Äã(x2)subscriptùêµsubscriptŒõsubscriptùîΩ2subscriptùë•2B_{*}=\Lambda_{\mathbb{F}_{2}}(x_{2}) (with |x2|=2subscriptùë•22|x_{2}|=2) but A‚àósubscriptùê¥A_{*} and B‚àósubscriptùêµB_{*} are not quasi-isomorphic. You find more examples and proofs in [31, ¬ß¬ß4,5].

We cannot expect that commutative ùêªùëÖùêªùëÖ\mathit{HR}-algebra spectra correspond to commutative differential graded RùëÖR-algebras unless RùëÖR is of characteristic zero, because of cohomology operations, but we get the following result:

Theorem 3.5.

[98, Corollary 8.3] ‚Äâ Let RùëÖR be a commutative ring. Then there is a chain of Quillen equivalences between the model category of commutative ùêªùëÖùêªùëÖ\mathit{HR}-algebra spectra and E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-monoids in the category of unbounded RùëÖR-chain complexes.

Haldun √ñzg√ºr Bayƒ±ndƒ±r shows [21] that one can find E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-differential graded algebras that are not quasi-isomorphic, but whose corresponding commutative ùêªùëÖùêªùëÖ\mathit{HR}-algebra spectra are equivalent as commutative ring spectra.

3.2. Cochain algebras

A prominent class of examples of commutative ùêªùëÖùêªùëÖ\mathit{HR}-algebra spectra consists of function spectra F‚Äã(X+,ùêªùëÖ)ùêπsubscriptùëãùêªùëÖF(X_{+},\mathit{HR}). Here, XùëãX is an arbitrary space and RùëÖR is a commutative ring. The diagonal Œî:X‚ÜíX√óX:Œî‚Üíùëãùëãùëã\Delta\colon X\rightarrow X\times X and the multiplication on ùêªùëÖùêªùëÖ\mathit{HR}, ŒºùêªùëÖsubscriptùúáùêªùëÖ\mu_{\mathit{HR}}, induce a multiplication

that turns F‚Äã(X+,ùêªùëÖ)ùêπsubscriptùëãùêªùëÖF(X_{+},\mathit{HR}) into a ùêªùëÖùêªùëÖ\mathit{HR}-algebra spectrum. As the diagonal is cocommutative and as ŒºùêªùëÖsubscriptùúáùêªùëÖ\mu_{\mathit{HR}} is commutative, the resulting multiplication is commutative.

These function spectra are models for the singular cochains of a space XùëãX with coefficients in RùëÖR:

œÄ‚àó‚Äã(F‚Äã(X+,ùêªùëÖ))‚âÖH‚àí‚àó‚Äã(X;R).subscriptùúãùêπsubscriptùëãùêªùëÖsuperscriptùêªabsentùëãùëÖ\pi_{*}(F(X_{+},\mathit{HR}))\cong H^{-*}(X;R).

Beware that the homotopy groups of F‚Äã(X+,ùêªùëÖ)ùêπsubscriptùëãùêªùëÖF(X_{+},\mathit{HR}) are concentrated in non-positive degrees ‚Äì i.e., F‚Äã(X+,ùêªùëÖ)ùêπsubscriptùëãùêªùëÖF(X_{+},\mathit{HR}) is coconnective.

Studying the singular cochains of a space S‚àó‚Äã(X;R)superscriptùëÜùëãùëÖS^{*}(X;R) as a differential graded RùëÖR-module is not enough in order to recover the homotopy type of XùëãX. If we work over the rational numbers, then Quillen showed that rational homotopy theory is algebraic in the sense that one can use rational differential graded Lie algebras or coalgebras as models for rational homotopy theory [94]. Sullivan [118] constructed a functor, assigning a rational differential graded commutative algebra to a space, that is closely related to the singular cochain functor with rational coefficients. He used this to classify rational homotopy types.

For a general commutative ring RùëÖR, the singular cochains are an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-algebra. Mike Mandell proves [72, Main Theorem] that the singular cochain functor with coefficients in an algebraic closure of ùîΩpsubscriptùîΩùëù\mathbb{F}_{p}, ùîΩ¬Øpsubscript¬ØùîΩùëù\bar{\mathbb{F}}_{p}, induces an equivalence between the homotopy category of connected pùëùp-complete nilpotent spaces of finite pùëùp-type and a full subcategory of the homotopy category of E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ùîΩ¬Øpsubscript¬ØùîΩùëù\bar{\mathbb{F}}_{p}-algebras. He also characterizes those E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ùîΩ¬Øpsubscript¬ØùîΩùëù\bar{\mathbb{F}}_{p}-algebras that arise as cochain algebras of 111-connected pùëùp-complete spaces of finity pùëùp-type explicitly [72, Characterization Theorem]. There is also an integral version of this result, stating that finite type nilpotent spaces are weakly equivalent if and only if their E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-algebras of integral cochains are quasi-isomorphic [74, Main Theorem].

4. Units of ring spectra and Thom spectra

One construction that can give rise to highly structured multiplications on a spectrum is the Thom spectrum construction: For instance, complex bordism, M‚ÄãUùëÄùëàMU, obtains a commutative ring structure this way. Early on Mahowald emphasized [71] that multiplicatve properties of the structure maps for Thom spectra translate to multiplicative structures on the resulting Thom spectra. Their properties and the corresponding orientation theory is systematically studied in [81]. There is the following general result by Lewis:

Theorem 4.1.

[64, Theorem IX.7.1 and Remark IX.7.2] ‚Äâ Assume that fùëìf is a map of spaces from XùëãX to the classifying space for stable spherical fibrations, B‚ÄãGùêµùê∫BG, that is a ùíûùíû\mathcal{C}-map for some operad ùíûùíû\mathcal{C} over the linear isometries operad. Then the Thom spectrum M‚Äã(f)ùëÄùëìM(f) associated to fùëìf carries a ùíûùíû\mathcal{C}-structure. In particular, infinite loops maps from XùëãX to B‚ÄãGùêµùê∫BG give rise to E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring spectra.

Note that B‚ÄãGùêµùê∫BG is the classifying space of the units of the sphere spectrum, G‚ÄãL1‚Äã(S)ùê∫subscriptùêø1ùëÜGL_{1}(S). A naive definition of G‚ÄãL1‚Äã(S)ùê∫subscriptùêø1ùëÜGL_{1}(S) is given by the pullback of the diagram

(4.1)

so by the components of Q‚ÄãS0ùëÑsuperscriptùëÜ0QS^{0} corresponding to ¬±1‚àà‚Ñ§plus-or-minus1‚Ñ§\pm 1\in\mathbb{Z}.

In the following we give a short overview of Thom spectra that arise in a more general context, where the target of the map is the space of units, G‚ÄãL1‚Äã(R)ùê∫subscriptùêø1ùëÖGL_{1}(R), for a commutative ring spectrum RùëÖR. The first idea is to define the space G‚ÄãL1‚Äã(R)ùê∫subscriptùêø1ùëÖGL_{1}(R) as the space that represents the functor that sends a space XùëãX to the units in R0‚Äã(X)superscriptùëÖ0ùëãR^{0}(X). Copying the definition from (4.1) above with SùëÜS replaced by RùëÖR gives a valid first definition of G‚ÄãL1‚Äã(R)ùê∫subscriptùêø1ùëÖGL_{1}(R) and it was shown [81] that for commutative RùëÖR this model is an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-space.

In the approaches [1] and [20], the idea is to replace the naive model of G‚ÄãL1‚Äã(R)ùê∫subscriptùêø1ùëÖGL_{1}(R) with its E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-structure with a strictly commutative model. As spaces with an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-structure are not equivalent to strictly commutative spaces (that‚Äôs the problem again that then Q‚ÄãS0ùëÑsuperscriptùëÜ0QS^{0} would be a product of Eilenberg-Mac‚ÄâLane spaces [90]), one has to find a different category with the property that there is a Quillen equivalence between commutative monoids in that category and E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-monoids in spaces and such that there are models of Œ©‚àû‚Äã(R)superscriptŒ©ùëÖ\Omega^{\infty}(R) and G‚ÄãL1‚Äã(R)ùê∫subscriptùêø1ùëÖGL_{1}(R) in this category.

In [1] the authors work with ‚àó‚àó\ast-modules and in [20] the authors use Schlichtkrull‚Äôs model of G‚ÄãL1‚Äã(R)ùê∫subscriptùêø1ùëÖGL_{1}(R) in commutative IùêºI-spaces where IùêºI is the skeleton of the category of finite sets and injections.

The idea is to construct a spectrum version of the assembly map for discrete rings: If RùëÖR is a discrete ring and if R√ósuperscriptùëÖR^{\times} is its group of units, then there is a canonical map

(4.2) ‚Ñ§‚Äã[R√ó]‚ÜíR‚Üí‚Ñ§delimited-[]superscriptùëÖùëÖ\mathbb{Z}[R^{\times}]\rightarrow R

from the group ring ‚Ñ§‚Äã[R√ó]‚Ñ§delimited-[]superscriptùëÖ\mathbb{Z}[R^{\times}] to RùëÖR that takes an element ‚àëi=1nai‚Äãrisuperscriptsubscriptùëñ1ùëõsubscriptùëéùëñsubscriptùëüùëñ\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}r_{i} of ‚Ñ§‚Äã[R√ó]‚Ñ§delimited-[]superscriptùëÖ\mathbb{Z}[R^{\times}] (with ai‚àà‚Ñ§subscriptùëéùëñ‚Ñ§a_{i}\in\mathbb{Z} and ri‚ààR√ósubscriptùëüùëñsuperscriptùëÖr_{i}\in R^{\times}) to the same sum, but now we use the ring structure of RùëÖR to convert the formal sum into an actual sum ‚àëi=1nai‚Äãri‚ààRsuperscriptsubscriptùëñ1ùëõsubscriptùëéùëñsubscriptùëüùëñùëÖ\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}r_{i}\in R. Note that R√ósuperscriptùëÖR^{\times} is an abelian group if RùëÖR is a commutative ring.

We will sketch both constructions of Thom spectra and briefly discuss the application in [1] to the question when a Thom spectrum allows for an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-map to some other E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring spectrum, for instance, whether one can realize an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-version of the string orientation M‚ÄãO‚Äã‚ü®8‚ü©‚ÜíùóçùóÜùñø‚ÜíùëÄùëÇdelimited-‚ü®‚ü©8ùóçùóÜùñøMO\langle 8\rangle\rightarrow\mathsf{tmf} [3] or an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-version of a complex orientation [49].

The focus in [20] is on multiplicative properties of the Thom spectrum functor and on applications to topological Hochschild homology. We present the results about multiplicative structures and discuss their results on ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH} of Thom spectra in Section 6. We‚Äôll also describe how the concept of IùêºI-spaces can be generalized to a setting in which the units can be adapted to non-connective ring spectra.

An important example is the question of the string orientation of the spectrum of topological modular forms, ùóçùóÜùñøùóçùóÜùñø\mathsf{tmf}. by showing a fiber property as above.

An approach to orientations of the form M‚ÄãU‚ÜíE‚ÜíùëÄùëàùê∏MU\rightarrow E is described in [49]: You start with an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty} ring spectrum Eùê∏E and an ordinary complex orientation of Eùê∏E [97, ¬ß6.1] and want to know whether you can refine this to an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-map M‚ÄãU‚ÜíE‚ÜíùëÄùëàùê∏MU\rightarrow E. and for a given E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-map M‚ÄãXn‚ÜíE‚ÜíùëÄsubscriptùëãùëõùê∏MX_{n}\rightarrow E they identify the space of extensions to an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-map M‚ÄãXn+1‚ÜíE‚ÜíùëÄsubscriptùëãùëõ1ùê∏MX_{n+1}\rightarrow E [49, Theorem 1].

Remark 4.7.

In [1] the authors present a different approach to Thom spectra and questions about orientations that uses ‚àû\infty-categorical techniques. In certain cases it is unrealistic to hope for E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-maps out of Thom spectra, for instance if one doesn‚Äôt know that the target spectrum carries an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty} structure. The space of Ensubscriptùê∏ùëõE_{n}-maps out of Thom spectra is described in [29, Theorem 4.2], [7, Corollary 3.18].

4.2. Thom spectra via IùêºI-spaces

Let IùêºI be the skeleton of the category of finite sets and injective maps. As objects we choose the sets ùêß={1,‚Ä¶,n}ùêß1‚Ä¶ùëõ\mathbf{n}=\{1,\ldots,n\} for n‚©æ0ùëõ0n\geqslant 0 with the convention that ùüé0\mathbf{0} denotes the empty set. A morphism f‚ààI‚Äã(ùêß,ùê¶)ùëìùêºùêßùê¶f\in I(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m}) is an injective function from ùêßùêß\mathbf{n} to ùê¶ùê¶\mathbf{m}. Hence ùüé0\mathbf{0} is an initial object of IùêºI and the permutation group Œ£nsubscriptŒ£ùëõ\Sigma_{n} is the group of automorphisms of ùêßùêß\mathbf{n} in IùêºI. The category IùêºI is symmetric monoidal with respect to the disjoint union: ùêß‚äîùê¶=ùêß+ùê¶square-unionùêßùê¶ùêßùê¶\mathbf{n}\sqcup\mathbf{m}=\mathbf{n+m} with unit ùüé0\mathbf{0} and non-trivial symmetry ùêß+ùê¶‚Üíùê¶+ùêß‚Üíùêßùê¶ùê¶ùêß\mathbf{n+m}\rightarrow\mathbf{m+n} given by the shuffle permutation that moves the first nùëõn elements to the positions m+1,‚Ä¶,m+nùëö1‚Ä¶ùëöùëõm+1,\ldots,m+n.

The functor category of IùêºI-spaces, ùñ≥ùóàùóâIsuperscriptùñ≥ùóàùóâùêº\mathsf{Top}^{I}, i.e., the category of functors X:I‚Üíùñ≥ùóàùóâ:ùëã‚Üíùêºùñ≥ùóàùóâX\colon I\rightarrow\mathsf{Top} together with natural transformations as morphisms, inherits a symmetric monoidal structure from IùêºI and ùñ≥ùóàùóâùñ≥ùóàùóâ\mathsf{Top} via the Day convolution product. Explicitly, one gets:

Definition 4.8.

Let X,YùëãùëåX,Y be two IùêºI-spaces. Their product X‚ä†Y‚ä†ùëãùëåX\boxtimes Y is the IùêºI-space given by

As ùüé0\mathbf{0} is initial, the unit 1Isubscript1ùêº1_{I} is the terminal object in ùñ≥ùóàùóâIsuperscriptùñ≥ùóàùóâùêº\mathsf{Top}^{I}. Commutative monoids in ùñ≥ùóàùóâIsuperscriptùñ≥ùóàùóâùêº\mathsf{Top}^{I} are called commutative IùêºI-space monoids in [20] and their category is denoted by C‚Äã(ùñ≥ùóàùóâI)ùê∂superscriptùñ≥ùóàùóâùêºC(\mathsf{Top}^{I}). A general fact about Day convolution products is that commutative monoids correspond to lax symmetric monoidal functors.

For an IùêºI-space XùëãX let‚Äôs denote by Xh‚ÄãIsubscriptùëã‚ÑéùêºX_{hI} the Bousfield-Kan homotopy colimit of XùëãX.

Definition 4.9.

With the corresponding IùêºI-model structure the category of IùêºI-spaces is actually Quillen equivalent to the category of spaces [107, Theorem 3.3], but there is a positive flat model structure on IùêºI-spaces (see [20, ¬ß2]) that lifts to a right-induced model structure on C‚Äã(ùñ≥ùóàùóâI)ùê∂superscriptùñ≥ùóàùóâùêºC(\mathsf{Top}^{I}) that makes it Quillen equivalent to E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-spaces.

Let ùñ≤ùóâŒ£superscriptùñ≤ùóâŒ£\mathsf{Sp}^{\Sigma} denote the category of symmetric spectra. There is a canonical Quillen adjoint functor pair

Stable equivalences in symmetric spectra do in general not agree with stable homotopy equivalences, but there is a notion of semistable symmetric spectra, that has the feature that a map f:E‚ÜíF:ùëì‚Üíùê∏ùêπf\colon E\rightarrow F between two semistable symmetric spectra is a stable equivalence if and only if it is a stable homotopy equivalence. If you don‚Äôt like diagram categories for some reason, then there is also an IùêºI-spacification functor [20, ¬ß4.1] that transforms a map of topological spaces

This construction respects actions of operads augmented over the Barratt-Eccles operad and hence it also provides an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty} Thom spectrum functor.

An important question is: Given a ring spectrum Aùê¥A, can it be realized as a Thom spectrum with respect to a loop map, i.e., in the setting of [20] is Aùê¥A equivalent to MI‚Äã(f)superscriptùëÄùêºùëìM^{I}(f) with fùëìf a loop map to B‚ÄãGh‚ÄãIùêµsubscriptùê∫‚ÑéùêºBG_{hI}? A striking result is that one can identify certain quotients as such Thom spectra!

Theorem 4.13.

[20, Theorem 5.6] ‚Äâ Let RùëÖR be a commutative ring spectrum whose homotopy groups are concentrated in even degrees and let ui‚ààœÄ2‚Äãi‚Äã(R)subscriptùë¢ùëñsubscriptùúã2ùëñùëÖu_{i}\in\pi_{2i}(R) be arbitrary elements with 1‚©Ωi‚©Ωn‚àí11ùëñùëõ11\leqslant i\leqslant n-1. Then the iterative cofiber of the multiplication maps by the uisubscriptùë¢ùëñu_{i}‚Äôs, R/(u1,‚Ä¶,un‚àí1)ùëÖsubscriptùë¢1‚Ä¶subscriptùë¢ùëõ1R/(u_{1},\ldots,u_{n-1}) can be realized as the Thom spectrum of a loop map from S‚ÄãU‚Äã(n)ùëÜùëàùëõSU(n) to B‚ÄãGh‚ÄãIùêµsubscriptùê∫‚ÑéùêºBG_{hI}. In particular, R/(u1,‚Ä¶,un‚àí1)ùëÖsubscriptùë¢1‚Ä¶subscriptùë¢ùëõ1R/(u_{1},\ldots,u_{n-1}) can be realized as an associative ring spectrum.

An example of such a quotient is R=k‚Äãu‚Üík‚Äãu/u=H‚Äã‚Ñ§ùëÖùëòùë¢‚Üíùëòùë¢ùë¢ùêª‚Ñ§R=ku\rightarrow ku/u=H\mathbb{Z}. Note that there is no assumption on the regularity of the elements uisubscriptùë¢ùëñu_{i} in the above statement. For periodic ring spectra the assumptions on the degree of the elements can be relaxed and the two-periodic version of Morava K-theory can be constructed as a Thom spectrum relative to R=EnùëÖsubscriptùê∏ùëõR=E_{n}, the nùëõn-th Morava Eùê∏E-theory or Lubin-Tate spectrum [20, Corollary 5.7]. A related but different construction of quotients of Lubin-Tate spectra modelling versions of Morava K-theory is carried out in [50, ¬ß3].

4.3. Graded units

There is one problem with the constructions of spaces and spectra of units as above. As they are constructed from the underlying infinite loop space of a spectrum and just take into account the units in œÄ0subscriptùúã0\pi_{0}, they ignore graded units coming from periodicity elements in the homotopy groups of a spectrum. So for instance, the Bott class u‚ààœÄ2‚Äã(ùêæùëà)ùë¢subscriptùúã2ùêæùëàu\in\pi_{2}(\mathit{KU}) is not represented in G‚ÄãL1‚Äã(ùêæùëà)ùê∫subscriptùêø1ùêæùëàGL_{1}(\mathit{KU}) or G‚ÄãL1I‚Äã(ùêæùëà)ùê∫superscriptsubscriptùêø1ùêºùêæùëàGL_{1}^{I}(\mathit{KU}).

There is a construction of graded units. We‚Äôll sketch the construction and mention two of its applications: graded Thom spectra and logarithmic ring spectra.

[107, 4.4, 4.5] ‚Äâ For every JùêΩJ-space XùëãX the homotopy colimit, Xh‚ÄãJsubscriptùëã‚ÑéùêΩX_{hJ}, is a space over Q‚ÄãS0ùëÑsuperscriptùëÜ0QS^{0}.

[107, Theorem 4.11] ‚Äâ There is a model structure on C‚Äã(ùñ≥ùóàùóâJ)ùê∂superscriptùñ≥ùóàùóâùêΩC(\mathsf{Top}^{J}) such that there is a Quillen equivalence between C‚Äã(ùñ≥ùóàùóâJ)ùê∂superscriptùñ≥ùóàùóâùêΩC(\mathsf{Top}^{J}) and the category of E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-spaces over B‚ÄãJùêµùêΩBJ.

For a (commutative) JùêΩJ-space monoid, one can associate units:

Definition 4.17.

[107, ¬ß4] ‚Äâ Let Aùê¥A be a JùêΩJ-space monoid. Remark 4.19.
  2. (a)

    John Rognes developed the concept of logarithmic ring spectra and in [106] and [105] this concept is fully explored with the help of graded units. The idea is that you want a spectrum that sits between a commutative ring spectrum like k‚Äãuùëòùë¢ku and its localization ùêæùëàùêæùëà\mathit{KU}, so you remember the Bott class as the extra datum of a logarithmic structure. This concept has its origin in algebraic geometry and is useful in stable homotopy theory for instance for obtaining localization sequences in topological Hochschild homology [105].

  3. (b)

    In [108] Sagave and Schlichtkrull use graded units adapted to the setting of orthogonal spectra, G‚ÄãL1Wùê∫superscriptsubscriptùêø1ùëäGL_{1}^{W}, to construct graded Thom spectra associated to virtual vector bundles, i.e., associated to a map f:X‚Üí‚Ñ§√óB‚ÄãO:ùëì‚Üíùëã‚Ñ§ùêµùëÇf\colon X\rightarrow\mathbb{Z}\times BO in such a way that uses the E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-structure on ‚Ñ§√óB‚ÄãO‚Ñ§ùêµùëÇ\mathbb{Z}\times BO. They use this for orientation theory and relate G‚ÄãL1Wùê∫superscriptsubscriptùêø1ùëäGL_{1}^{W}-orientations to logarithmic structures. They provide an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-Thom isomorphism that allows to compute the homology of spectra appearing in connection with logarithmic ring spectra [108, ¬ß¬ß‚Äâ 7,8].

5. Constructing commutative ring spectra from bipermutative categories

In section 4 we saw that Thom spectra give rise to commutative ring spectra. Algebraic K-theory is another machine that takes a commutative ring (spectrum) RùëÖR and produces a commutative ring spectrum K‚Äã(R)ùêæùëÖK(R). In this section we focus on a classical construction that takes a small bipermutative category ‚Ñõ‚Ñõ\mathcal{R} and turns it into a commutative ring spectrum. This construction goes back to Segal [114]; its multiplicative properties were investigated by May [81, 82, 83, 84], Shimada-Shimakawa [115], Woolfson [124] and Elmendorf-Mandell [35].

We sketch a simplified version of the construction, present some important examples and refer to [35] for a discussion of the multiplicative properties.

Segal shows [114, Corollary 2.2] that this construction gives rise to a so-called ŒìŒì\Gamma-space (see [114, Definition 1.2] for a definition) that sends a finite pointed set XùëãX to the classifying space of ùíû‚Äã(X)ùíûùëã\mathcal{C}(X). Every ŒìŒì\Gamma-space gives rise to a spectrum, and we denote the spectrum associated to ùíûùíû\mathcal{C} by H‚ÄãùíûùêªùíûH\mathcal{C}.

Remark 5.3.

Segal‚Äôs construction actually works for symmetric monoidal categories and it produces a spectrum whose associated infinite loop space is the group completion of the classifying space of the category ùíûùíû\mathcal{C}, B‚ÄãùíûùêµùíûB\mathcal{C}, and the latter is the geometric realization of the nerve of ùíûùíû\mathcal{C}.

Definition 5.4.

This definition is taken from [81, Definition VI.3.3, p.¬†154]. The definition in [35] is less strict, but bipermutative categories in the above sense are also bipermutative in the sense of [35, Definition 3.6]. We refer to Elmendorf and Mandell for a proof that for a bipermutative category ‚Ñõ‚Ñõ\mathcal{R}, one actually obtains a commutative ring spectrum H‚Äã‚Ñõùêª‚ÑõH\mathcal{R}:

Theorem 5.5.

[35, Corollary 3.9] ‚Äâ If ‚Ñõ‚Ñõ\mathcal{R} is a bipermutative category, then H‚Äã‚Ñõùêª‚ÑõH\mathcal{R} is equivalent to a strictly commutative symmetric ring spectrum.

Segal‚Äôs construction enables us to find small and explicit models for certain connective commutative ring spectra. Famous examples of bipermutative categories and their associated commutative ring spectra are the following:

  1. (a)

    If RùëÖR is a commutative discrete ring, then the category ‚ÑõRsubscript‚ÑõùëÖ\mathcal{R}_{R} which has the elements of RùëÖR as objects and only identity morphisms is a bipermutative category with the addition in the ring being ‚äïdirect-sum\oplus and the multiplication being ‚äótensor-product\otimes. The associated spectrum, H‚Äã‚ÑõRùêªsubscript‚ÑõùëÖH\mathcal{R}_{R} is the Eilenberg-Mac‚ÄâLane spectrum of the ring RùëÖR, ùêªùëÖùêªùëÖ\mathit{HR}.

  2. (b)

    Let ‚Ñ∞‚Ñ∞\mathcal{E} denote the bipermutative category of finite sets whose objects are the finite sets ùêß={1,‚Ä¶,n}ùêß1‚Ä¶ùëõ\mathbf{n}=\{1,\ldots,n\} for n‚àà‚Ñï0ùëõsubscript‚Ñï0n\in\mathbb{N}_{0}. By convention ùüé0\mathbf{0} is the empty set. The morphisms in ‚Ñ∞‚Ñ∞\mathcal{E} are

    ‚Ñ∞‚Äã(ùêß,ùê¶)={‚àÖ,n‚â†m,Œ£n,n=m.‚Ñ∞ùêßùê¶casesùëõùëösubscriptŒ£ùëõùëõùëö\mathcal{E}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m})=\left\{\begin{array}[]{cc}\varnothing,&n\neq m,\\ \Sigma_{n},&n=m.\end{array}\right.

    For the full structure see [81, VI, Example 5.1]. Here, H‚Äã‚Ñ∞ùêª‚Ñ∞H\mathcal{E} is the sphere spectrum, SùëÜS.

  3. (c)

    The bipermutative category of complex vector spaces, ùí±‚ÑÇsubscriptùí±‚ÑÇ\mathcal{V}_{\mathbb{C}}, with objects the natural numbers with zero and morphisms

    ùí±‚ÑÇ‚Äã(n,m)={‚àÖ,n‚â†m,U‚Äã(n),n=msubscriptùí±‚ÑÇùëõùëöcasesùëõùëöùëàùëõùëõùëö\mathcal{V}_{\mathbb{C}}(n,m)=\left\{\begin{array}[]{cc}\varnothing,&n\neq m,\\ U(n),&n=m\end{array}\right.

    is bipermutative. On objects we set n‚äïm=n+mdirect-sumùëõùëöùëõùëön\oplus m=n+m and n‚äóm=n‚Äãmtensor-productùëõùëöùëõùëön\otimes m=nm and on morphism we use the block sum and the tensor product of matrices. The associated spectrum is H‚Äãùí±‚ÑÇ=k‚Äãuùêªsubscriptùí±‚ÑÇùëòùë¢H\mathcal{V}_{\mathbb{C}}=ku, the connective version of topological complex K-theory. Its real analog, ùí±‚Ñùsubscriptùí±‚Ñù\mathcal{V}_{\mathbb{R}}, gives a model for connective topological real K-theory, k‚Äãoùëòùëúko. You can also work with the general linear group instead of the unitary or orthogonal group.

  4. (d)

    If RùëÖR is a discrete commutative ring, then we define the category FRsubscriptùêπùëÖF_{R} as the one with objects ‚Ñï0subscript‚Ñï0\mathbb{N}_{0} again. As morphisms we have

    FR‚Äã(n,m)={‚àÖ,n‚â†m,G‚ÄãLn‚Äã(R),n=m.subscriptùêπùëÖùëõùëöcasesùëõùëöùê∫subscriptùêøùëõùëÖùëõùëöF_{R}(n,m)=\begin{cases}\varnothing,&n\neq m,\\ GL_{n}(R),&n=m.\end{cases}

    This category is often called the small category of free RùëÖR-modules. Its spectrum is the free algebraic K-theory of RùëÖR, Kf‚Äã(R)superscriptùêæùëìùëÖK^{f}(R). Its homotopy groups agree with the algebraic K-groups of RùëÖR from degree 111 on.

6. From topological Hochschild to topological Andr√©-Quillen homology

For rings and algebras Hochschild homology contains a lot of information. For commutative rings and algebras Andr√©-Quillen homology is the adequate tool. There are spectrum level versions of these homology theories: topological Hochschild homology, ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH}, and topological Andr√©-Quillen homology, ùñ≥ùñ†ùñ∞ùñ≥ùñ†ùñ∞\mathsf{TAQ}.

We can determine classes in the algebraic K-theory of a ring spectrum using the trace to topological Hochschild homology or to topological cyclic homology:

(6.1) t‚Äãr:K‚Äã(R)‚Üíùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(R).:ùë°ùëü‚ÜíùêæùëÖùñ≥ùñßùñßùëÖtr\colon K(R)\rightarrow\mathsf{THH}(R).

For instance the trace from K‚Äã(‚Ñ§)ùêæ‚Ñ§K(\mathbb{Z}) to ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(‚Ñ§)ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Ñ§\mathsf{THH}(\mathbb{Z}) detects important classes. B√∂kstedt, Madsen and Rognes [26, 103] show for instance that

tr:K2‚Äãp‚àí1‚Äã(‚Ñ§)‚Üíùñ≥ùñßùñß2‚Äãp‚àí1‚Äã(‚Ñ§)‚âÖ‚Ñ§/p‚Äã‚Ñ§:tr‚Üísubscriptùêæ2ùëù1‚Ñ§subscriptùñ≥ùñßùñß2ùëù1‚Ñ§‚Ñ§ùëù‚Ñ§\text{tr}\colon K_{2p-1}(\mathbb{Z})\rightarrow\mathsf{THH}_{2p-1}(\mathbb{Z})\cong\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}

is surjective for all primes pùëùp.

We give a construction of topological Hochschild homology and more generally, for commutative ring spectra RùëÖR we define X‚äóRtensor-productùëãùëÖX\otimes R for XùëãX a finite pointed simplicial set. We give some examples of calculations of such XùëãX-homology groups of RùëÖR and tell you about topological Hochschild cohomology as a derived center of an algebra spectrum. We define topological Andr√©-Quillen homology and we will see applications to Postnikov towers for commutative ring spectra later in 7.

6.1. ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH} and friends

Let XùëãX be a finite pointed simplicial set and let RùëÖR be a cofibrant commutative ring spectrum.

Definition 6.1.

We denote by X‚äóRtensor-productùëãùëÖX\otimes R the simplicial spectrum with

(X‚äóR)n=‚ãÄx‚ààXnR.subscripttensor-productùëãùëÖùëõsubscriptùë•subscriptùëãùëõùëÖ(X\otimes R)_{n}=\bigwedge_{x\in X_{n}}R.

By slight abuse of notation we will use the same symbol for the geometric realization of X‚äóRtensor-productùëãùëÖX\otimes R.

Remark 6.2.
  • ‚Ä¢

    As the smash product is the coproduct in ùíûSsubscriptùíûùëÜ\mathcal{C}_{S}, the simplicial structure maps of X‚äóRtensor-productùëãùëÖX\otimes R are induced from the ones on XùëãX.

  • ‚Ä¢

    As XùëãX is pointed, X‚äóRtensor-productùëãùëÖX\otimes R comes with maps

    R‚ÜíX‚äóR‚ÜíR‚ÜíùëÖtensor-productùëãùëÖ‚ÜíùëÖR\rightarrow X\otimes R\rightarrow R

    whose composition is the identity.

  • ‚Ä¢

    The commutative multiplication on RùëÖR induces a commutative multiplication on X‚äóRtensor-productùëãùëÖX\otimes R, hence X‚äóRtensor-productùëãùëÖX\otimes R is an augmented commutative (simplicial) RùëÖR-algebra spectrum.

  • ‚Ä¢

    One could also work with the fact that the spectra of [34] are tensored over topological spaces or similarly, that symmetric spectra [54] in topological spaces are enriched over simplicial sets and over topological spaces. This gives an equivalent situation. It is for instance shown in [34, Corollary VII.3.4] that |X‚äóA|‚âÉ|X|‚äóAsimilar-to-or-equalstensor-productùëãùê¥tensor-productùëãùê¥|X\otimes A|\simeq|X|\otimes A for simplicial spaces XùëãX and commutative RùëÖR-algebra spectra Aùê¥A.

  • ‚Ä¢

    The above definition can be extended to tensoring with an arbitrary pointed simplicial sets by expressing such a simplicial set as the colimit of its finite pointed simplicial subcomplexes.

There are many important special cases of this construction.

Definition 6.3.
  2. (a)

    For the simplicial 111-sphere X=ùïä1ùëãsuperscriptùïä1X=\mathbb{S}^{1} the commutative RùëÖR-algebra spectrum ùïä1‚äóRtensor-productsuperscriptùïä1ùëÖ\mathbb{S}^{1}\otimes R is the topological Hochschild homology of RùëÖR and is denoted by ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(R)ùñ≥ùñßùñßùëÖ\mathsf{THH}(R).

  3. (b)

    More generally, for an nùëõn-sphere, we denote by ùñ≥ùñßùñß[n]‚Äã(R)superscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßdelimited-[]ùëõùëÖ\mathsf{THH}^{[n]}(R) the spectrum ùïän‚äóRtensor-productsuperscriptùïäùëõùëÖ\mathbb{S}^{n}\otimes R and this is called topological Hochschild homology of order nùëõn.

  4. (c)

    If ùïãnsuperscriptùïãùëõ\mathbb{T}^{n} denotes the torus (ùïä1)nsuperscriptsuperscriptùïä1ùëõ(\mathbb{S}^{1})^{n}, then ùïãn‚äóRtensor-productsuperscriptùïãùëõùëÖ\mathbb{T}^{n}\otimes R is the nùëõn-torus homology of RùëÖR.

For the small model of the simplicial 111-sphere with just one non-degenerate 00 and 111 simplex we have (ùïä1)n={0,1,‚Ä¶,n}subscriptsuperscriptùïä1ùëõ01‚Ä¶ùëõ(\mathbb{S}^{1})_{n}=\{0,1,\ldots,n\} and the simplicial spectrum ùïä1‚äóRtensor-productsuperscriptùïä1ùëÖ\mathbb{S}^{1}\otimes R is precisely the cyclic bar construction on RùëÖR:

where the degeneracy map si:Rn+1‚ÜíRn+2:subscriptùë†ùëñ‚ÜísuperscriptùëÖùëõ1superscriptùëÖùëõ2s_{i}\colon R^{n+1}\rightarrow R^{n+2} inserts the unit map Œ∑:S‚ÜíR:ùúÇ‚ÜíùëÜùëÖ\eta\colon S\rightarrow R after the iùëñith factor of RùëÖR and the face maps di:Rn+1‚ÜíRn:subscriptùëëùëñ‚ÜísuperscriptùëÖùëõ1superscriptùëÖùëõd_{i}\colon R^{n+1}\rightarrow R^{n} for 0‚©Ωi<n0ùëñùëõ0\leqslant i<n are given by the multiplication in RùëÖR of the iùëñith and (i+1)ùëñ1(i+1)st smash factor. The last face map dnsubscriptùëëùëõd_{n} cyclically permutes the smash factors to bring the last one to the front and then it multiplies the former factors with number nùëõn and 00.

As for Hochschild homology you should think about this as a genuine cyclic object:

The original definition of ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH} is due to Marcel B√∂kstedt [24]. McClure, Schw√§nzl and Vogt [86] show that for an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring spectrum RùëÖR, ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(R)ùñ≥ùñßùñßùëÖ\mathsf{THH}(R), is equivalent to tensoring RùëÖR with the topological 111-sphere. Kuhn systematically studies constructions like X‚äóRtensor-productùëãùëÖX\otimes R in a reduced setting [60] for pointed spaces XùëãX. So the above definition is an unreduced variant of this that uses simplicial sets instead of topological spaces.

Lemma 6.4.

Let XùëãX and YùëåY be finite simplicial pointed sets. Then

(X√óY)‚äóR‚âÉX‚äó(Y‚äóR).similar-to-or-equalstensor-productùëãùëåùëÖtensor-productùëãtensor-productùëåùëÖ(X\times Y)\otimes R\simeq X\otimes(Y\otimes R).
Proof.

Observe that

((X√óY)‚äóR)n=‚ãÄ(x,y)‚ààXn√óYnR‚âÖ‚ãÄx‚ààXn(‚ãÄy‚ààYnR)subscripttensor-productùëãùëåùëÖùëõsubscriptùë•ùë¶subscriptùëãùëõsubscriptùëåùëõùëÖsubscriptùë•subscriptùëãùëõsubscriptùë¶subscriptùëåùëõùëÖ((X\times Y)\otimes R)_{n}=\bigwedge_{(x,y)\in X_{n}\times Y_{n}}R\cong\bigwedge_{x\in X_{n}}(\bigwedge_{y\in Y_{n}}R)

and this is the diagonal of the bisimplicial spectrum

([m],[‚Ñì])‚Ü¶(X‚äó((Y‚äóR)‚Ñì))mmaps-todelimited-[]ùëödelimited-[]‚Ñìsubscripttensor-productùëãsubscripttensor-productùëåùëÖ‚Ñìùëö([m],[\ell])\mapsto(X\otimes((Y\otimes R)_{\ell}))_{m}

in degree nùëõn. ‚àé

One of the important features of ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(R)ùñ≥ùñßùñßùëÖ\mathsf{THH}(R) is that it receives a trace map from algebraic K-theory (see (6.1)) that we can now write as

t‚Äãr:K‚Äã(R)‚Üíùïä1‚äóR.:ùë°ùëü‚ÜíùêæùëÖtensor-productsuperscriptùïä1ùëÖtr\colon K(R)\rightarrow\mathbb{S}^{1}\otimes R.

Taking higher dimensional tori gives targets for iterated trace maps. Algebraic K-theory of a commutative ring spectrum is again a commutative ring spectrum and the trace map is a map of commutative ring spectra, hence one can iterate the process of forming K-theory and traces. If we denote by Kn‚Äã(R)superscriptùêæùëõùëÖK^{n}(R) the nùëõn-fold iteration, then ‚Äì as we have the product formula from Lemma 6.4 ‚Äì we get an iterated trace to ùïãn‚äóRtensor-productsuperscriptùïãùëõùëÖ\mathbb{T}^{n}\otimes R. Explicitly, for n=2ùëõ2n=2 this is

K‚Äã(K‚Äã(R))‚Üíùïä1‚äó(ùïä1‚äóR)‚âÉ(ùïä1√óùïä1)‚äóR=ùïã2‚äóR.‚ÜíùêæùêæùëÖtensor-productsuperscriptùïä1tensor-productsuperscriptùïä1ùëÖsimilar-to-or-equalstensor-productsuperscriptùïä1superscriptùïä1ùëÖtensor-productsuperscriptùïã2ùëÖK(K(R))\rightarrow\mathbb{S}^{1}\otimes(\mathbb{S}^{1}\otimes R)\simeq(\mathbb{S}^{1}\times\mathbb{S}^{1})\otimes R=\mathbb{T}^{2}\otimes R.

There are variants of Definition 6.1: As we work with pointed simplicial sets, we can glue an RùëÖR-module to the base point and use the RùëÖR-module structure for the face maps. A second variant is to work relative to some commutative ring spectrum RùëÖR: In 6.1 the smash products were over the sphere spectrum, but if we work with a commutative RùëÖR-algebra spectrum Aùê¥A, then we can take smash products over RùëÖR instead of SùëÜS. Recall that ‚àßRsubscriptùëÖ\wedge_{R} is the coproduct in the category of commutative RùëÖR-algebra spectra, ùíûRsubscriptùíûùëÖ\mathcal{C}_{R}.

Definition 6.5.

Let RùëÖR be a cofibrant commutative ring spectrum, Aùê¥A a cofibrant commutative RùëÖR-algebra spectrum, MùëÄM an Aùê¥A-module spectrum over RùëÖR and let XùëãX be a finite pointed simplicial set. We denote by ‚ÑíXR‚Äã(A;M)subscriptsuperscript‚ÑíùëÖùëãùê¥ùëÄ\mathcal{L}^{R}_{X}(A;M) the simplicial spectrum with

‚ÑíXR‚Äã(A;M)n=M‚àßR‚ãÄx‚ààXn‚àñ‚Å£‚àóR‚ÄãA.subscriptsuperscript‚ÑíùëÖùëãsubscriptùê¥ùëÄùëõsubscriptùëÖùëÄsubscriptùë•limit-fromsubscriptùëãùëõsubscriptùëÖùê¥\mathcal{L}^{R}_{X}(A;M)_{n}=M\wedge_{R}{\bigwedge_{x\in X_{n}\setminus*}}\raisebox{-5.0pt}{}_{\!\!\!\!\!\!R}A.

We call ‚ÑíXR‚Äã(A;M)subscriptsuperscript‚ÑíùëÖùëãùê¥ùëÄ\mathcal{L}^{R}_{X}(A;M) the Loday construction of Aùê¥A over RùëÖR with coefficients in MùëÄM.

As MùëÄM is just an Aùê¥A-module spectrum, the resulting simplicial spectrum and also its realization carries an Aùê¥A-module structure over RùëÖR, but no multiplicative structure in general. However, if we place a commutative Aùê¥A-algebra Cùê∂C at the basepoint, then the resulting spectrum is an augmented commutative Cùê∂C-algebra spectrum.

We will see later in Section 8 that for instance

ùñ≥ùñßùñßR‚Äã(A):=‚Ñíùïä1R‚Äã(A)assignsuperscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßùëÖùê¥subscriptsuperscript‚ÑíùëÖsuperscriptùïä1ùê¥\mathsf{THH}^{R}(A):=\mathcal{L}^{R}_{\mathbb{S}^{1}}(A)

measures properties of Aùê¥A as a commutative RùëÖR-algebra spectrum. The case of X=ùïä0ùëãsuperscriptùïä0X=\mathbb{S}^{0} gives

‚Ñíùïä0R‚Äã(A)=A‚àßRAsubscriptsuperscript‚ÑíùëÖsuperscriptùïä0ùê¥subscriptùëÖùê¥ùê¥\mathcal{L}^{R}_{\mathbb{S}^{0}}(A)=A\wedge_{R}A

so there is a K√ºnneth spectral sequence [34, IV.4.1] for calculating its homotopy groups.

An important example of a Loday construction is Pirashvili‚Äôs construction of higher order Hochschild homology. He works with discrete commutative kùëòk-algebras Aùê¥A and Aùê¥A-modules MùëÄM and defines ùñßùñßXk‚Äã(A;M)superscriptsubscriptùñßùñßùëãùëòùê¥ùëÄ\mathsf{HH}_{X}^{k}(A;M) [92, ¬ß5.1]. For X=ùïänùëãsuperscriptùïäùëõX=\mathbb{S}^{n} this is his notion of higher order Hochschild homology (in his notation H[n]‚Äã(A;M)superscriptùêªdelimited-[]ùëõùê¥ùëÄH^{[n]}(A;M)). In our setting this corresponds to ‚ÑíXH‚Äãk‚Äã(ùêªùê¥;H‚ÄãM)subscriptsuperscript‚Ñíùêªùëòùëãùêªùê¥ùêªùëÄ\mathcal{L}^{H\!k}_{X}(\mathit{HA};H\!M) if Aùê¥A is flat over kùëòk.

6.2. Examples

  1. (a)

    A classical example of a ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH}-calculation is the one of H‚Äã‚Ñ§ùêª‚Ñ§\mathit{H}\!\mathbb{Z} and H‚ÄãùîΩpùêªsubscriptùîΩùëùH\mathbb{F}_{p} by Marcel B√∂kstedt ([25], see [67, Chapter 13] and the references for published accounts of these results):

    Proposition 6.6.
    ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚àó‚Äã(H‚ÄãùîΩp)‚âÖùîΩp‚Äã[Œº],|Œº|=2.formulae-sequencesubscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßùêªsubscriptùîΩùëùsubscriptùîΩùëùdelimited-[]ùúáùúá2\mathsf{THH}_{*}(H\mathbb{F}_{p})\cong\mathbb{F}_{p}[\mu],\quad|\mu|=2.
    ùñ≥ùñßùñßi‚Äã(H‚Äã‚Ñ§)‚âÖ{‚Ñ§,i=0,‚Ñ§/j‚Äã‚Ñ§,i=2‚Äãj‚àí1,0,¬†otherwise.¬†subscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßùëñùêª‚Ñ§cases‚Ñ§ùëñ0‚Ñ§ùëó‚Ñ§ùëñ2ùëó10¬†otherwise.¬†\mathsf{THH}_{i}(\mathit{H}\!\mathbb{Z})\cong\begin{cases}\mathbb{Z},&i=0,\\ \mathbb{Z}/j\mathbb{Z},&i=2j-1,\\ 0,&\text{ otherwise. }\end{cases}

    A crucial ingredient for these and for many other calculations of ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH} is B√∂kstedt‚Äôs spectral sequence: If RùëÖR is a commutative ring spectrum and if E‚àósubscriptùê∏E_{*} is a homotopy commutative ring spectrum such that E‚àó‚Äã(R)subscriptùê∏ùëÖE_{*}(R) is flat over E‚àósubscriptùê∏E_{*} then there is a multiplicative spectral sequence

    Ep,q2=ùñßùñßp,qE‚àó‚Äã(E‚àó‚Äã(R))‚áíEp+q‚Äãùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(R).subscriptsuperscriptùê∏2ùëùùëûsubscriptsuperscriptùñßùñßsubscriptùê∏ùëùùëûsubscriptùê∏ùëÖ‚áísubscriptùê∏ùëùùëûùñ≥ùñßùñßùëÖE^{2}_{p,q}=\mathsf{HH}^{E_{*}}_{p,q}(E_{*}(R))\Rightarrow E_{p+q}\mathsf{THH}(R).

    Here ùñßùñßp,qsubscriptùñßùñßùëùùëû\mathsf{HH}_{p,q} denotes Hochschild homology in homological degree pùëùp and internal degree qùëûq ([25], [34, Theorem IV.1.9]).

  2. (b)

    If we apply ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH} to Eilenberg-Mac‚ÄâLane spectra of number rings, Lindenstrauss and Madsen show that ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH} detects arithmetic properties:

    Proposition 6.7.

    [66, Theorem 1.1] ‚Äâ Let KùêæK be a number field and let ùí™Ksubscriptùí™ùêæ\mathcal{O}_{K} be its ring of integers. Then

    ùñ≥ùñßùñßn‚Äã(H‚Äãùí™K)={ùí™K,n=0,ùíüùí™K‚àí1/‚Ñì‚Äãùí™K,n=2‚Äã‚Ñì‚àí1,0,otherwise.subscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßùëõùêªsubscriptùí™ùêæcasessubscriptùí™ùêæùëõ0superscriptsubscriptùíüsubscriptùí™ùêæ1‚Ñìsubscriptùí™ùêæùëõ2‚Ñì10otherwise.\mathsf{THH}_{n}(H\!\mathcal{O}_{K})=\begin{cases}\mathcal{O}_{K},&n=0,\\ \mathcal{D}_{\mathcal{O}_{K}}^{-1}/\ell\mathcal{O}_{K},&n=2\ell-1,\\ 0,&\text{otherwise.}\end{cases}

    Here, ùíüùí™K‚àí1superscriptsubscriptùíüsubscriptùí™ùêæ1\mathcal{D}_{\mathcal{O}_{K}}^{-1} is the inverse different. This is the set of all x‚ààKùë•ùêæx\in K such that the trace t‚Äãr‚Äã(x‚Äãy)ùë°ùëüùë•ùë¶tr(xy) is an integer for all y‚ààùí™Kùë¶subscriptùí™ùêæy\in\mathcal{O}_{K}. The inverse different detects ramified primes and their ramification type.

    We calculate higher order ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH} of number rings with reduced coefficients in [32, Theorem 4.3].

  3. (c)

    For a suspension spectrum on a based (Moore) loop space, Œ£+‚àû‚ÄãŒ©M‚ÄãXsubscriptsuperscriptŒ£subscriptŒ©ùëÄùëã\Sigma^{\infty}_{+}\Omega_{M}X, the cyclic bar construction reduces to the suspension spectrum of the cyclic bar construction on Œ©M‚ÄãXsubscriptŒ©ùëÄùëã\Omega_{M}X and Goodwillie [40, Proof of Theorem V.1.1] identifies the latter with the free loop space on XùëãX, L‚ÄãXùêøùëãLX.     ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(Œ£+‚àû‚ÄãŒ©M‚ÄãX)‚âÉŒ£+‚àû‚ÄãL‚ÄãX.similar-to-or-equalsùñ≥ùñßùñßsubscriptsuperscriptŒ£subscriptŒ©ùëÄùëãsubscriptsuperscriptŒ£ùêøùëã\mathsf{THH}(\Sigma^{\infty}_{+}\Omega_{M}X)\simeq\Sigma^{\infty}_{+}LX.
  4. (d)

    Let RùëÖR be a ring spectrum and let Œ†Œ†\Pi be a pointed monoid. Hesselholt and Madsen show that ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(R‚Äã[Œ†])ùñ≥ùñßùñßùëÖdelimited-[]Œ†\mathsf{THH}(R[\Pi]) splits as

    ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(R‚Äã[Œ†])‚âÉùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(R)‚àß|Nc‚Äãy‚ÄãŒ†|similar-to-or-equalsùñ≥ùñßùñßùëÖdelimited-[]Œ†ùñ≥ùñßùñßùëÖsuperscriptùëÅùëêùë¶Œ†\mathsf{THH}(R[\Pi])\simeq\mathsf{THH}(R)\wedge|N^{cy}\Pi|

    where |Nc‚Äãy‚ÄãŒ†|superscriptùëÅùëêùë¶Œ†|N^{cy}\Pi| denotes the cyclic nerve of Œ†Œ†\Pi [45, Theorem 7.1].

  5. (e)

    As a sample calculation for second order ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH} we get [33, Theorem 2.1]:

    (6.2) ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚àó[2]‚Äã(H‚Äã‚Ñ§(p))‚âÖ‚Ñ§(p)‚Äã[x1,x2,‚Ä¶]/(pn‚Äãxn,xnp‚àíp‚Äãxn+1,n‚©æ1)subscriptsuperscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßdelimited-[]2ùêªsubscript‚Ñ§ùëùsubscript‚Ñ§ùëùsubscriptùë•1subscriptùë•2‚Ä¶superscriptùëùùëõsubscriptùë•ùëõsuperscriptsubscriptùë•ùëõùëùùëùsubscriptùë•ùëõ1ùëõ1\mathsf{THH}^{[2]}_{*}(H\mathbb{Z}_{(p)})\cong\mathbb{Z}_{(p)}[x_{1},x_{2},\ldots]/(p^{n}x_{n},x_{n}^{p}-px_{n+1},n\geqslant 1)

    with |x1|=2‚Äãpsubscriptùë•12ùëù|x_{1}|=2p.

  6. (f)

    At an odd prime ùêæùëà(p)subscriptùêæùëàùëù\mathit{KU}_{\!\!(p)} splits as

    ùêæùëà(p)‚âÉ‚ãÅi=0p‚àí2Œ£2‚Äãi‚ÄãL.similar-to-or-equalssubscriptùêæùëàùëùsuperscriptsubscriptùëñ0ùëù2superscriptŒ£2ùëñùêø\mathit{KU}_{\!\!(p)}\simeq\bigvee_{i=0}^{p-2}\Sigma^{2i}L.

    Here, LùêøL is the Adams summand of ùêæùëà(p)subscriptùêæùëàùëù\mathit{KU}_{\!\!(p)} with œÄ‚àó‚Äã(L)‚âÖ‚Ñ§(p)‚Äã[v1¬±1]subscriptùúãùêøsubscript‚Ñ§ùëùdelimited-[]superscriptsubscriptùë£1plus-or-minus1\pi_{*}(L)\cong\mathbb{Z}_{(p)}[v_{1}^{\pm 1}] and |v1|=2‚Äãp‚àí2subscriptùë£12ùëù2|v_{1}|=2p-2. For consistency we set L=ùêæùëà(2)ùêøsubscriptùêæùëà2L=\mathit{KU}_{\!\!(2)} at the prime 222. We denote by ùëòùë¢ùëòùë¢\mathit{ku}, ‚Ñì‚Ñì\ell and ùëòùëúùëòùëú\mathit{ko} the connective covers of ùêæùëàùêæùëà\mathit{KU}, LùêøL and ùêæùëÇùêæùëÇ\mathit{KO}.

    McClure and Staffeldt determine the mod pùëùp-homotopy of ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(‚Ñì)ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Ñì\mathsf{THH}(\ell) at odd primes [88] and they show that ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(L)p‚âÉLp‚à®(Œ£‚ÄãLp)‚Ñösimilar-to-or-equalsùñ≥ùñßùñßsubscriptùêøùëùsubscriptùêøùëùsubscriptŒ£subscriptùêøùëù‚Ñö\mathsf{THH}(L)_{p}\simeq L_{p}\vee(\Sigma L_{p})_{\mathbb{Q}} [88, Corollary 7.2, Theorem 8.1].

    Ausoni [9] determines the mod pùëùp and mod v1subscriptùë£1v_{1} homotopy of ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(k‚Äãu)ùñ≥ùñßùñßùëòùë¢\mathsf{THH}(ku) as an input for his work on K‚Äã(k‚Äãu)ùêæùëòùë¢K(ku).

    Angeltveit, Hill and Lawson show [5, Theorem 2.6] that for all primes, as an ‚Ñì‚àósubscript‚Ñì\ell_{*}-module

    ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚àó‚Äã(‚Ñì)‚âÖ‚Ñì‚àó‚äïŒ£2‚Äãp‚àí1‚ÄãF‚äïTsubscriptùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Ñìdirect-sumsubscript‚ÑìsuperscriptŒ£2ùëù1ùêπùëá\mathsf{THH}_{*}(\ell)\cong\ell_{*}\oplus\Sigma^{2p-1}F\oplus T

    where FùêπF is a torsionfree summand and TùëáT is an infinite direct sum of torsion modules concentrated in even degrees. They describe FùêπF explicitly using a rational calculation. Determining the torsion is way more involved [5, Theorem 2.8]. The calculation of ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚àó‚Äã(‚Ñì)subscriptùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Ñì\mathsf{THH}_{*}(\ell) uses the method of duelling Bockstein spectral sequences for the Bockstein spectral sequences associated to

    They describe the 222-local homotopy groups of ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(k‚Äão)ùñ≥ùñßùñßùëòùëú\mathsf{THH}(ko) [5, ¬ß7] by first determining ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚àó‚Äã(k‚Äão;k‚Äãu)subscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßùëòùëúùëòùë¢\mathsf{THH}_{*}(ko;ku) and then using the Bockstein spectral sequence associated to the cofiber sequence Œ£‚Äãk‚Äão‚Üík‚Äão‚Üík‚Äãu‚ÜíŒ£ùëòùëúùëòùëú‚Üíùëòùë¢\Sigma ko\rightarrow ko\rightarrow ku.

    Again, things are way easier for the periodic versions [9, Proposition 7.13], [5, Corollary 7.9]:

    ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(ùêæùëÇ)‚âÉùêæùëÇ‚à®Œ£‚ÄãùêæùëÇ‚Ñö,ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(K‚ÄãU)‚âÉK‚ÄãU‚à®Œ£‚Äãùêæùëà‚Ñö.formulae-sequencesimilar-to-or-equalsùñ≥ùñßùñßùêæùëÇùêæùëÇŒ£subscriptùêæùëÇ‚Ñösimilar-to-or-equalsùñ≥ùñßùñßùêæùëàùêæùëàŒ£subscriptùêæùëà‚Ñö\mathsf{THH}(\mathit{KO})\simeq\mathit{KO}\vee\Sigma\mathit{KO}_{\mathbb{Q}},\quad\mathsf{THH}(KU)\simeq KU\vee\Sigma\mathit{KU}_{\mathbb{Q}}.
  7. (g)

    John Greenlees uses a generalization of the concept of Gorenstein maps of commutative rings to the spectral world in order to determine Gorenstein descent properties for cofiber sequences of connective commutative ring spectra [42, Theorem 7.4].

6.3. Topological Hochschild homology of Thom spectra

We start with a general statement about X‚äóMI‚Äã(f)tensor-productùëãsuperscriptùëÄùêºùëìX\otimes M^{I}(f) if MI‚Äã(f)superscriptùëÄùêºùëìM^{I}(f) is a Thom spectrum associated to an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-map to B‚ÄãGh‚ÄãIùêµsubscriptùê∫‚ÑéùêºBG_{hI} with B‚ÄãGh‚ÄãIùêµsubscriptùê∫‚ÑéùêºBG_{hI} as in (4.8) with R=SùëÖùëÜR=S, hence Gùê∫G is a cofibrant replacement of G‚ÄãL1I‚Äã(S)ùê∫superscriptsubscriptùêø1ùêºùëÜGL_{1}^{I}(S).

Theorem 6.8.

[109, Theorem 1.1] ‚Äâ For any pointed simplicial set XùëãX and any map of grouplike E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-spaces f:A‚ÜíB‚ÄãGh‚ÄãI:ùëì‚Üíùê¥ùêµsubscriptùê∫‚Ñéùêºf\colon A\rightarrow BG_{hI} there is an equivalence of E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring spectra

X‚äóMI‚Äã(f)‚âÉMI‚Äã(f)‚àßŒ©‚àû‚Äã(a‚àß|X|)+similar-to-or-equalstensor-productùëãsuperscriptùëÄùêºùëìsuperscriptùëÄùêºùëìsuperscriptŒ©subscriptùëéùëãX\otimes M^{I}(f)\simeq M^{I}(f)\wedge\Omega^{\infty}(a\wedge|X|)_{+}

where aùëéa is the spectrum associated to Aùê¥A with Œ©‚àû‚Äãa=AsuperscriptŒ©ùëéùê¥\Omega^{\infty}a=A.

This result generalizes [22], where the case of X=ùïä1ùëãsuperscriptùïä1X=\mathbb{S}^{1} is covered. In general, for X=ùïänùëãsuperscriptùïäùëõX=\mathbb{S}^{n} the above result determines the higher order topological Hochschild homology of MI‚Äã(f)superscriptùëÄùêºùëìM^{I}(f) [109, (1.6)] as

ùñ≥ùñßùñß[n]‚Äã(MI‚Äã(f))‚âÉMI‚Äã(f)‚àßBn‚ÄãA+.similar-to-or-equalssuperscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßdelimited-[]ùëõsuperscriptùëÄùêºùëìsuperscriptùëÄùêºùëìsuperscriptùêµùëõsubscriptùê¥\mathsf{THH}^{[n]}(M^{I}(f))\simeq M^{I}(f)\wedge B^{n}A_{+}.

As an example consider the canonical map f:B‚ÄãU‚ÜíB‚ÄãGh‚ÄãI:ùëì‚Üíùêµùëàùêµsubscriptùê∫‚Ñéùêºf\colon BU\rightarrow BG_{hI}. Then one obtains

X‚äóM‚ÄãU‚âÉM‚ÄãU‚àßŒ©‚àû‚Äã(b‚Äãu‚àß|X|)similar-to-or-equalstensor-productùëãùëÄùëàùëÄùëàsuperscriptŒ©ùëèùë¢ùëãX\otimes MU\simeq MU\wedge\Omega^{\infty}(bu\wedge|X|)

and

ùñ≥ùñßùñß[n]‚Äã(M‚ÄãU)‚âÉM‚ÄãU‚àßŒ©‚àû‚Äã(b‚Äãu‚àßùïän)‚âÉM‚ÄãU‚àßBn‚ÄãB‚ÄãU+.similar-to-or-equalssuperscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßdelimited-[]ùëõùëÄùëàùëÄùëàsuperscriptŒ©ùëèùë¢superscriptùïäùëõsimilar-to-or-equalsùëÄùëàsuperscriptùêµùëõùêµsubscriptùëà\mathsf{THH}^{[n]}(MU)\simeq MU\wedge\Omega^{\infty}(bu\wedge\mathbb{S}^{n})\simeq MU\wedge B^{n}BU_{+}.

There is also a statement about ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH} of Thom spectra associated to single loop maps in [22, Theorem 1]. We state the relative version of this, so Gùê∫G is a cofibrant replacement of G‚ÄãL1I‚Äã(R)ùê∫superscriptsubscriptùêø1ùêºùëÖGL_{1}^{I}(R).

Theorem 6.9.
