by reducing the loop coordinates by precomposition.

For quotient spectra, this results gives a new way of calculating ùñ≥ùñßùñßR‚Äã(R/I)superscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßùëÖùëÖùêº\mathsf{THH}^{R}(R/I). For related results see [4] and in the case where R/IùëÖùêºR/I happens to be commutative see [33, ¬ß7].

A second example comes from viewing H‚Äã‚Ñ§(p)ùêªsubscript‚Ñ§ùëùH\mathbb{Z}_{(p)} as a Thom spectrum associated as a 222-fold loop map Œ©2‚Äã(ùïä3‚Äã‚ü®3‚ü©)‚ÜíB‚ÄãGh‚ÄãI‚ÜísuperscriptŒ©2superscriptùïä3delimited-‚ü®‚ü©3ùêµsubscriptùê∫‚Ñéùêº\Omega^{2}(\mathbb{S}^{3}\langle 3\rangle)\rightarrow BG_{hI} which allows for a determination of ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(H‚Äã‚Ñ§(p))ùñ≥ùñßùñßùêªsubscript‚Ñ§ùëù\mathsf{THH}(H\mathbb{Z}_{(p)}) as H‚Äã‚Ñ§(p)‚àßŒ©‚Äã(ùïä3‚Äã‚ü®3‚ü©)+ùêªsubscript‚Ñ§ùëùŒ©subscriptsuperscriptùïä3delimited-‚ü®‚ü©3H\mathbb{Z}_{(p)}\wedge\Omega(\mathbb{S}^{3}\langle 3\rangle)_{+} [22, Theorem 3.8] and an additive equivalence

ùñ≥ùñßùñß[2]‚Äã(H‚Äã‚Ñ§(p))‚âÉH‚Äã‚Ñ§(p)‚àßùïä3‚Äã‚ü®3‚ü©+.similar-to-or-equalssuperscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßdelimited-[]2ùêªsubscript‚Ñ§ùëùùêªsubscript‚Ñ§ùëùsuperscriptùïä3subscriptdelimited-‚ü®‚ü©3\mathsf{THH}^{[2]}(H\mathbb{Z}_{(p)})\simeq H\mathbb{Z}_{(p)}\wedge\mathbb{S}^{3}\langle 3\rangle_{+}.

This gives a geometric interpretation of (6.2), but without an identification of the multiplicative structure. See also [59, ¬ß4], where Klang presents related results, using the framework of factorization homology.

6.4. Topological Hochschild cohomology as a derived center

In the discrete case, i.e., for a commutative ring kùëòk and a kùëòk-algebra Aùê¥A one can describe the center of Aùê¥A,

Z‚Äã(A)={b‚ààA,a‚Äãb=b‚Äãa‚Äã¬†for all¬†‚Äãa‚ààA}ùëçùê¥formulae-sequenceùëèùê¥ùëéùëèùëèùëé¬†for all¬†ùëéùê¥Z(A)=\{b\in A,ab=ba\text{ for all }a\in A\}

as the set of Aùê¥A-bimodule maps from Aùê¥A to Aùê¥A. If fùëìf is such a map, f:A‚ÜíA:ùëì‚Üíùê¥ùê¥f\colon A\rightarrow A with f‚Äã(c‚Äãa‚Äãd)=c‚Äãf‚Äã(a)‚Äãdùëìùëêùëéùëëùëêùëìùëéùëëf(cad)=cf(a)d for all a,c,d‚ààAùëéùëêùëëùê¥a,c,d\in A, then fùëìf is determined by f(1)=:bf(1)=:b and this bùëèb satisfies

a‚Äãb=a‚Äãf‚Äã(1)=f‚Äã(a‚ãÖ1)=f‚Äã(a)=f‚Äã(1‚ãÖa)=f‚Äã(1)‚Äãa=b‚Äãaùëéùëèùëéùëì1ùëì‚ãÖùëé1ùëìùëéùëì‚ãÖ1ùëéùëì1ùëéùëèùëéab=af(1)=f(a\cdot 1)=f(a)=f(1\cdot a)=f(1)a=ba

so the set of such morphisms gives rise to an element in the center and vice versa, for any b‚ààZ‚Äã(A)ùëèùëçùê¥b\in Z(A) we get such an fùëìf by setting f‚Äã(1)=bùëì1ùëèf(1)=b.

Hochschild cohomology of Aùê¥A over kùëòk can be described as

ùñßùñßk‚àó‚Äã(A)=ùñ§ùóëùóçA‚äókAo‚àó‚Äã(A,A)subscriptsuperscriptùñßùñßùëòùê¥subscriptsuperscriptùñ§ùóëùóçsubscripttensor-productùëòùê¥superscriptùê¥ùëúùê¥ùê¥\mathsf{HH}^{*}_{k}(A)=\mathsf{Ext}^{*}_{A\otimes_{k}A^{o}}(A,A)

if Aùê¥A is kùëòk-projective. Hence ùñßùñßk0‚Äã(A)=Z‚Äã(A)subscriptsuperscriptùñßùñß0ùëòùê¥ùëçùê¥\mathsf{HH}^{0}_{k}(A)=Z(A) and the Hochschild cohomology of Aùê¥A is the derived center of Aùê¥A. Hochschild cohomology has a graded commutative algebra structure via a cup product, but the solved Deligne conjecture [87] says that the Hochschild cochain complex is in general not a differential graded commutative algebra, but that it has an E2subscriptùê∏2E_{2}-algebra structure.

For ring spectra there is no homotopically meaningful definition of a center: requiring equality translates to an equalizer diagram and this wouldn‚Äôt be homotopy invariant. For a commutative ring spectrum RùëÖR and an RùëÖR-algebra spectrum Aùê¥A this equalizer corresponds precisely to taking not just RùëÖR-module endomorphisms but Aùê¥A-bimodule endomorphisms. So a homotopy invariant version is as follows.

Definition 6.10.

For a commutative ring spectrum RùëÖR and an RùëÖR-algebra spectrum Aùê¥A, the topological Hochschild cohomology groups of Aùê¥A over RùëÖR are

ùñ≥ùñßùñßR‚àó‚Äã(A)=œÄ‚àó‚Äãùñ§ùóëùóçA‚àßRAo‚Äã(A,A)superscriptsubscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßùëÖùê¥subscriptùúãsubscriptùñ§ùóëùóçsubscriptùëÖùê¥superscriptùê¥ùëúùê¥ùê¥\mathsf{THH}_{R}^{*}(A)=\pi_{*}\mathsf{Ext}_{A\wedge_{R}A^{o}}(A,A)

and the derived center of Aùê¥A over RùëÖR is

ùñ≥ùñßùñßR‚Äã(A)=ùñ§ùóëùóçA‚àßRAo‚Äã(A,A).subscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßùëÖùê¥subscriptùñ§ùóëùóçsubscriptùëÖùê¥superscriptùê¥ùëúùê¥ùê¥\mathsf{THH}_{R}(A)=\mathsf{Ext}_{A\wedge_{R}A^{o}}(A,A).

Here, ùñ§ùóëùóçA‚àßRAo‚Äã(A,A)subscriptùñ§ùóëùóçsubscriptùëÖùê¥superscriptùê¥ùëúùê¥ùê¥\mathsf{Ext}_{A\wedge_{R}A^{o}}(A,A) denotes the derived endomorphism spectrum of Aùê¥A as an Aùê¥A-bimodule [34, IV ¬ß1].

McClure and Smith‚Äôs proof of the Deligne conjecture also provides a spectrum version for topological Hochschild cohomology, giving the derived center an E2subscriptùê∏2E_{2}-structure:

Theorem 6.11.

[87] ‚Äâ If Aùê¥A is an associative RùëÖR-algebra spectrum, then ùñ≥ùñßùñßR‚Äã(A)subscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßùëÖùê¥\mathsf{THH}_{R}(A) is an E2subscriptùê∏2E_{2}-ring spectrum.

6.5. Topological Andr√©-Quillen homology

We will first sketch the definition of ordinary Andr√©-Quillen homology. See [95] for the original account and [55] for a very readable modern introduction.

Definition 6.13.

Let kùëòk be a commutative ring with unit and let Aùê¥A be a commutative kùëòk-algebra. The Aùê¥A-module of K√§hler differentials of Aùê¥A over kùëòk is the Aùê¥A-module generated by elements d‚Äã(a)ùëëùëéd(a) for a‚ààAùëéùê¥a\in A subject to the relations that dùëëd is kùëòk-linear and satisfies the Leibniz rule:

d‚Äã(a‚Äãb)=d‚Äã(a)‚Äãb+a‚Äãd‚Äã(b).ùëëùëéùëèùëëùëéùëèùëéùëëùëèd(ab)=d(a)b+ad(b).

This Aùê¥A-module is denoted by Œ©A|k1subscriptsuperscriptŒ©1conditionalùê¥ùëò\Omega^{1}_{A|k}.

The conditions imply d‚Äã(1)=d‚Äã(1‚ãÖ1)=2‚Äãd‚Äã(1)ùëë1ùëë‚ãÖ112ùëë1d(1)=d(1\cdot 1)=2d(1) and hence d‚Äã(1)=0ùëë10d(1)=0. For a polynomial algebra A=k‚Äã[x1,‚Ä¶,xn]ùê¥ùëòsubscriptùë•1‚Ä¶subscriptùë•ùëõA=k[x_{1},\ldots,x_{n}] the Aùê¥A-module Œ©k‚Äã[x1,‚Ä¶,xn]|k1subscriptsuperscriptŒ©1conditionalùëòsubscriptùë•1‚Ä¶subscriptùë•ùëõùëò\Omega^{1}_{k[x_{1},\ldots,x_{n}]|k} is freely generated by d‚Äãx1,‚Ä¶,d‚Äãxnùëësubscriptùë•1‚Ä¶ùëësubscriptùë•ùëõdx_{1},\ldots,dx_{n}. By induction one can show that d‚Äã(xim)=m‚Äãxim‚àí1‚Äãd‚Äã(xi)ùëësuperscriptsubscriptùë•ùëñùëöùëösuperscriptsubscriptùë•ùëñùëö1ùëësubscriptùë•ùëñd(x_{i}^{m})=mx_{i}^{m-1}d(x_{i}) for all m‚©æ2ùëö2m\geqslant 2.

Consider for instance the ùîΩpsubscriptùîΩùëù\mathbb{F}_{p}-algebra ùîΩp‚Äã[x]/(xp‚àíx)subscriptùîΩùëùdelimited-[]ùë•superscriptùë•ùëùùë•\mathbb{F}_{p}[x]/(x^{p}-x). and hence Œ©ùîΩp‚Äã[x]/(xp‚àíx)|ùîΩp1=0subscriptsuperscriptŒ©1conditionalsubscriptùîΩùëùdelimited-[]ùë•superscriptùë•ùëùùë•subscriptùîΩùëù0\Omega^{1}_{\mathbb{F}_{p}[x]/(x^{p}-x)|\mathbb{F}_{p}}=0.

Remark 6.14.

For a commutative kùëòk-algebra Aùê¥A there is an isomorphism between Œ©A|k1subscriptsuperscriptŒ©1conditionalùê¥ùëò\Omega^{1}_{A|k} and the first Hochschild homology group of Aùê¥A over kùëòk: Every a‚äóbtensor-productùëéùëèa\otimes b in Hochschild chain degree one is a cycle and if you send a‚äóbtensor-productùëéùëèa\otimes b to a‚Äãd‚Äã(b)ùëéùëëùëèad(b) then this gives a well-defined map modulo Hochschild boundaries and it induces an isomorphism ùñßùñß1k‚Äã(A)‚âÖŒ©A|k1subscriptsuperscriptùñßùñßùëò1ùê¥subscriptsuperscriptŒ©1conditionalùê¥ùëò\mathsf{HH}^{k}_{1}(A)\cong\Omega^{1}_{A|k} [67, Proposition 1.1.10].

Definition 6.15.

Let MùëÄM be an Aùê¥A-module. A kùëòk-linear derivation from Aùê¥A to MùëÄM is a kùëòk-linear map Œ¥:A‚ÜíM:ùõø‚Üíùê¥ùëÄ\delta\colon A\rightarrow M which satisfies the Leibniz rule.

The set of all such derivations, ùñ£ùñæùóãk‚Äã(A,M)subscriptùñ£ùñæùóãùëòùê¥ùëÄ\mathsf{Der}_{k}(A,M), is an Aùê¥A-submodule of the Aùê¥A-module of all kùëòk-linear maps. The symbol dùëëd in the definition of Œ©A|k1subscriptsuperscriptŒ©1conditionalùê¥ùëò\Omega^{1}_{A|k} satisfies the conditions of a derivation, hence the map

is a derivation, in fact, it is the universal derivation:

Proposition 6.16.

[55] ‚Äâ For all Aùê¥A-modules MùëÄM the canonical map

ùñßùóàùóÜA‚Äã(Œ©A|k1,M)‚Üíùñ£ùñæùóãk‚Äã(A,M),f‚Ü¶f‚àòdformulae-sequence‚ÜísubscriptùñßùóàùóÜùê¥subscriptsuperscriptŒ©1conditionalùê¥ùëòùëÄsubscriptùñ£ùñæùóãùëòùê¥ùëÄmaps-toùëìùëìùëë\mathsf{Hom}_{A}(\Omega^{1}_{A|k},M)\rightarrow\mathsf{Der}_{k}(A,M),\quad f\mapsto f\circ d

is an Aùê¥A-linear isomorphism.

There is another crucial reformulation of the above isomorphism: ùñ£ùñæùóãk‚Äã(A,M)subscriptùñ£ùñæùóãùëòùê¥ùëÄ\mathsf{Der}_{k}(A,M) can also be identified with the morphisms of commutative kùëòk-algebras from Aùê¥A to the square-zero extension A‚äïMdirect-sumùê¥ùëÄA\oplus M. The latter is the commutative Aùê¥A-algebra with underlying module A‚äïMdirect-sumùê¥ùëÄA\oplus M with multiplication

(a1,m1)‚Äã(a2,m2)=(a1‚Äãa2,a1‚Äãm2+a2‚Äãm1),a1,a2‚ààA,m1,m2‚ààM.formulae-sequencesubscriptùëé1subscriptùëö1subscriptùëé2subscriptùëö2subscriptùëé1subscriptùëé2subscriptùëé1subscriptùëö2subscriptùëé2subscriptùëö1subscriptùëé1formulae-sequencesubscriptùëé2ùê¥subscriptùëö1subscriptùëö2ùëÄ(a_{1},m_{1})(a_{2},m_{2})=(a_{1}a_{2},a_{1}m_{2}+a_{2}m_{1}),\quad a_{1},a_{2}\in A,m_{1},m_{2}\in M.

A derivation Œ¥:A‚ÜíM:ùõø‚Üíùê¥ùëÄ\delta\colon A\rightarrow M corresponds to the map into the second component of A‚äïMdirect-sumùê¥ùëÄA\oplus M.

The idea of Andr√©-Quillen homology is to take the derived funtor of A‚Ü¶M‚äóAŒ©A|k1maps-toùê¥subscripttensor-productùê¥ùëÄsubscriptsuperscriptŒ©1conditionalùê¥ùëòA\mapsto M\otimes_{A}\Omega^{1}_{A|k}. But in which sense? As Aùê¥A is a commutative algebra, we need a resolution of Aùê¥A as such an algebra. The category of differential graded commutative kùëòk-algebras in general doesn‚Äôt have a (right-induced) model structure, so instead one works with simplicial resolutions. The category of simplicial commutative kùëòk-algebras does have a nice model structure. Let P‚àô‚ÜíA‚ÜísubscriptùëÉ‚àôùê¥P_{\bullet}\rightarrow A be a cofibrant resolution. Each PnsubscriptùëÉùëõP_{n} can be chosen to be a polynomial algebra [55, ¬ß4].

Definition 6.17.

The Andr√©-Quillen homology of Aùê¥A over kùëòk with coefficients in MùëÄM is

ùñ†ùñ∞‚àó(A|k:M)=œÄ‚àó(M‚äóP‚àôŒ©P‚àô|k1).\mathsf{AQ}_{*}(A|k:M)=\pi_{*}(M\otimes_{P_{\bullet}}\Omega^{1}_{P_{\bullet}|k}).

A definition of Œ©A|k1subscriptsuperscriptŒ©1conditionalùê¥ùëò\Omega^{1}_{A|k} in terms of generators and relations is not suitable for a generalization to commutative ring spectra. Instead we use the following description:

Lemma 6.18.

Denote by IùêºI the kernel of the multiplication map

Then Œ©A|k1subscriptsuperscriptŒ©1conditionalùê¥ùëò\Omega^{1}_{A|k} is isomorphic to I/I2ùêºsuperscriptùêº2I/I^{2}.

Proof.

Note that IùêºI is generated by elements of the form a‚äó1‚àí1‚äóatensor-productùëé1tensor-product1ùëéa\otimes 1-1\otimes a. Such an element is identified with d‚Äã(a)ùëëùëéd(a). Taking the quotient by I2superscriptùêº2I^{2} corresponds to the Leibniz rule for dùëëd. ‚àé

The ideal IùêºI can also be viewed as a non-unital kùëòk-algebra and I/I2ùêºsuperscriptùêº2I/I^{2} is the module of indecomposables of IùêºI.

This definition translates to brave new commutative rings. Basterra‚Äôs work is formulated in the setting of [34]:

7. How do we recognize ring spectra as being (non) commutative?

If you have a concrete model of a homotopy type, say in symmetric spectra, then you can be lucky and this model posseses a commutative structure and you should be able to check this by hand. Of course you could also try to disprove commutativity by showing that your spectrum doesn‚Äôt have power operations as in (2.2) and this has been done in many cases, but sometimes you might need a different approach.

7.1. Obstructions via filtrations and resolutions

An obstruction theory for A‚àûsubscriptùê¥A_{\infty}-structures on homotopy ring spectra was developed as early as 1989 [100] by Alan Robinson. Obstruction theories for E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-structures came much later: Goerss-Hopkins and Robinson [38], [101] independently developed one with obstruction groups that later turned out to be isomorphic [19]. The idea is to use a filtration or resolution of an operad such that the corresponding filtration quotients or the corresponding spectral sequence gives rise to obstruction groups that contain obstructions for lifting a partial structure to a full E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring structure [101, Theorem 5.6], [38, Corollary 5.9]. The Goerss-Hopkins approach also allows to calculate the homotopy groups of the derived E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty} mapping space between two such E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring spectra [38, Theorem 4.5].

The obstruction groups have as input the algebra of cooperations E‚àó‚ÄãEsubscriptùê∏ùê∏E_{*}E of a spectrum Eùê∏E and they compute Andr√©-Quillen cohomology groups of the graded commutative E‚àósubscriptùê∏E_{*}-algebra E‚àó‚ÄãEsubscriptùê∏ùê∏E_{*}E in the setting of differential graded (or simplicial) E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-algebras. See [73], [39, ¬ß2.4] for background on these cohomology groups and see [19, ¬ß2] for the comparison results. In Robinson‚Äôs setting these groups are called Gamma-cohomology. The obstruction groups vanish if for instance E‚àó‚ÄãEsubscriptùê∏ùê∏E_{*}E is √©tale as an E‚àósubscriptùê∏E_{*}-algebra.

If you prefer to work with explicit chain complexes, then there are several equivalent ones computing Gamma cohomology groups in Robinson‚Äôs setting [101, ¬ß2.5], [102, ¬ß6], [93, ¬ß2] and therefore, by the comparison result from [19, Theorem 2.6], computing the obstruction groups in the Goerss-Hopkins setting as well.

There is another version of obstruction theory for promoting a homotopy TùëáT-algebra structure to an actual one by Johnson and Noel [58] where TùëáT is a monad. This includes obstructions for operadic structures on spectra but also includes for instance group actions. Noel shows that in certain situations the obstruction theory [58] can be compared to the one of [38].

We list some important applications:

  1. (a)

    The development of the Hopkins-Miller and Goerss-Hopkins obstruction theory was motivated by the Morava-Eùê∏E-theory spectra, also known as Lubin-Tate spectra, Ensubscriptùê∏ùëõE_{n} and variants of those. These are Landweber exact cohomology theories that govern the deformation theory of height nùëõn formal group laws. In [97] an obstruction theory was established that allowed to show that the Ensubscriptùê∏ùëõE_{n} are A‚àûsubscriptùê¥A_{\infty} spectra and that the Morava stabilizer group ùîænsubscriptùîæùëõ\mathbb{G}_{n} acts on Ensubscriptùê∏ùëõE_{n} via maps of A‚àûsubscriptùê¥A_{\infty} spectra. In [38] the corresponding obstruction theory for E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-structures was developed and [38, Corollaries 7.6, 7.7] shows that the ùîænsubscriptùîæùëõ\mathbb{G}_{n}-action is via E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-maps.

  2. (b)

    It was known that ùêæùëàùêæùëà\mathit{KU} and ùêæùëÇùêæùëÇ\mathit{KO} are E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-spectra and it was also known that the pùëùp-completed Adams summand LpsubscriptùêøùëùL_{p} is E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}. In [12] Andy Baker and I use Robinson‚Äôs version of the E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-obstruction theory to show that these E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-structures are unique and that the pùëùp-local Adams summand also has a unique E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-structure. Uniqueness also holds for the connective covers [14]. It is important to have uniqueness results for E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-structures because calculations can depend on a choice of such a structure.

  3. (c)

    For an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring spectrum RùëÖR there is a Œ∏ùúÉ\theta-algebra structure on its pùëùp-adic K-theory, œÄ‚àó‚ÄãLK‚Äã(1)‚Äã(K‚ÄãUp‚àßR)subscriptùúãsubscriptùêøùêæ1ùêæsubscriptùëàùëùùëÖ\pi_{*}L_{K(1)}(KU_{p}\wedge R) [39, Theorem 2.2.4] and in good cases

    œÄ‚àó‚ÄãLK‚Äã(1)‚Äã(K‚ÄãUp‚àßR)‚âÖlimk(K‚ÄãUp)‚àó‚Äã(R‚àßM‚Äã(pk))subscriptùúãsubscriptùêøùêæ1ùêæsubscriptùëàùëùùëÖsubscriptùëòsubscriptùêæsubscriptùëàùëùùëÖùëÄsuperscriptùëùùëò\pi_{*}L_{K(1)}(KU_{p}\wedge R)\cong\lim_{k}(KU_{p})_{*}(R\wedge M(p^{k}))

    where M‚Äã(pk)ùëÄsuperscriptùëùùëòM(p^{k}) is the mod-pksuperscriptùëùùëòp^{k} Moore spectrum. The study of such structures was initiated by McClure in [28, Chapter IX]. There is a variant of the Goerss-Hopkins obstruction theory for realizing for instance a Œ∏ùúÉ\theta-algebra (see [39, ¬ß2.4.4] and [63, Theorem 5.14]) as a K‚Äã(1)ùêæ1K(1)-local E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring spectrum.

    There is one for realizing an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-H‚ÄãkùêªùëòH\!k-algebra spectrum with a fixed Dyer-Lashof structure on its homotopy [91, Proposition 2.2] (for kùëòk a field of characteristic pùëùp). Other variants can be found in the literature.

    The Œ∏ùúÉ\theta-algebra version was successfully applied by Lawson and Naumann [63] to show that ùêµùëÉ‚Äã‚ü®2‚ü©ùêµùëÉdelimited-‚ü®‚ü©2\mathit{BP}\langle 2\rangle at 222 has an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-structure. By a different method Hill and Lawson [46, Theorem 4.2] find a commutative model for ùêµùëÉ‚Äã‚ü®2‚ü©ùêµùëÉdelimited-‚ü®‚ü©2\mathit{BP}\langle 2\rangle at the prime 333.

  4. (d)

    Mathew, Naumann and Noel use operations in Morava-Eùê∏E-theory to prove May‚Äôs nilpotence conjecture:

    Theorem 7.1.

    [79, Theorem A] ‚Äâ If RùëÖR is an H‚àûsubscriptùêªH_{\infty}-ring spectrum and if x‚ààœÄ‚àó‚Äã(R)ùë•subscriptùúãùëÖx\in\pi_{*}(R) is in the kernel of the Hurewicz homomorphism œÄ‚àó‚Äã(R)‚ÜíH‚àó‚Äã(R;‚Ñ§)‚ÜísubscriptùúãùëÖsubscriptùêªùëÖ‚Ñ§\pi_{*}(R)\rightarrow H_{*}(R;\mathbb{Z}), then xùë•x is nilpotent.

    They use this ‚Äì among many other applications ‚Äì for the following result about E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring spectra:

    Theorem 7.2.

    [79, Proposition 4.2] ‚Äâ If RùëÖR is an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring spectrum and if there is an m‚àà‚Ñ§ùëö‚Ñ§m\in\mathbb{Z}, m‚â†0ùëö0m\neq 0 with m‚ãÖ1=0‚ààœÄ0‚Äã(R)‚ãÖùëö10subscriptùúã0ùëÖm\cdot 1=0\in\pi_{0}(R), then for all primes pùëùp and for all n‚©æ1ùëõ1n\geqslant 1:

    K‚Äã(n)‚àó‚Äã(R)‚âÖ0.ùêæsubscriptùëõùëÖ0K(n)_{*}(R)\cong 0.

    Lawson observed that using K‚Äã(n)ùêæùëõK(n)-techniques (see [96] for background) this implies that for finite E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-ring spectra RùëÖR either the rational homology is non-trivial or RùëÖR is weakly contractible, because if H‚àó‚Äã(R;‚Ñö)‚âÖ0subscriptùêªùëÖ‚Ñö0H_{*}(R;\mathbb{Q})\cong 0, then by the above result all the Morava K-theories also vanish on RùëÖR, but then the finiteness of RùëÖR implies weak contractibility (see [79, Remark 4.3] for the full argument).

The Dyer-Lashof variant is for instance important when one wants to decide whether a given H‚àûsubscriptùêªH_{\infty}-map can be upgraded to an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-map: Roughly speaking, an H‚àûsubscriptùêªH_{\infty}-spectrum is like an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-spectrum in the homotopy category. You can find applications of this approach for instance in Noel‚Äôs work [91] and in [58].

Other spectra, for instance, ùêµùëÉùêµùëÉ\mathit{BP}, come with homology operations just because they sit in the right place: analyzing the maps ùëÄùëà‚ÜíùêµùëÉ‚ÜíH‚ÄãùîΩp‚ÜíùëÄùëàùêµùëÉ‚ÜíùêªsubscriptùîΩùëù\mathit{MU}\rightarrow\mathit{BP}\rightarrow H\mathbb{F}_{p} gives [28, p.¬†63] that (H‚ÄãùîΩp)‚àó‚Äã(ùêµùëÉ)subscriptùêªsubscriptùîΩùëùùêµùëÉ(H\mathbb{F}_{p})_{*}(\mathit{BP}) embeds into the dual of the Steenrod algebra such that (H‚ÄãùîΩp)‚àó‚Äã(ùêµùëÉ)subscriptùêªsubscriptùîΩùëùùêµùëÉ(H\mathbb{F}_{p})_{*}(\mathit{BP}) is closed under the action of the Dyer-Lashof algebra ‚Äì even without establishing a structured multiplication on ùêµùëÉùêµùëÉ\mathit{BP}. This led Lawson [61] to look for the right obstructions for an E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-structure of ùêµùëÉùêµùëÉ\mathit{BP} at 222 via secondary operations (see Theorem 7.5).

7.2. Obstructions via Postnikov towers

A different approach to obstruction theory is to consider Postnikov towers in the world of commutative ring spectra [16] or in the setting of Ensubscriptùê∏ùëõE_{n}-algebras [18].

[18, Theorem 1.1] ‚Äâ The Brown Peterson spectrum, ùêµùëÉùêµùëÉ\mathit{BP}, has an E4subscriptùê∏4E_{4}-structure at every prime.

[61, Theorem 1.1.2] ‚Äâ The Brown-Peterson spectrum at the prime 222 does not possess an Ensubscriptùê∏ùëõE_{n}-structure for any nùëõn with 12‚©Ωn‚©Ω‚àû12ùëõ12\leqslant n\leqslant\infty. 7.3. Realization of E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-spectra via derived algebraic geometry

There is a completely different important and highly successful approach to realization problems, namely using derived algebraic geometry. You can learn about derived algebraic geometry in the next Chapter of the book.

8. What are √©tale maps?

We first recall the algebraic notion of an √©tale kùëòk-algebra from [67, E.1]: Let kùëòk be a commutative ring and let Aùê¥A be a finitely generated commutative kùëòk-algebra. Then Aùê¥A is √©tale, if Aùê¥A is flat over kùëòk and if the module of K√§hler differentials Œ©A|k1subscriptsuperscriptŒ©1conditionalùê¥ùëò\Omega^{1}_{A|k} is trivial. If Œ©A|k1=0subscriptsuperscriptŒ©1conditionalùê¥ùëò0\Omega^{1}_{A|k}=0, then k‚ÜíA‚Üíùëòùê¥k\rightarrow A is called unramified. A kùëòk-algebra BùêµB (not necessarily commutative) is called separable, if the multiplication map

B‚äókBo‚ÜíB‚Üísubscripttensor-productùëòùêµsuperscriptùêµùëúùêµB\otimes_{k}B^{o}\rightarrow B

has a section as a BùêµB-bimodule map. In algebra, a commutative separable algebra has Hochschild homology concentrated in homological degree zero, in particular the module of K√§hler differentials is trivial.

8.1. Rognes‚Äô Galois extensions of commutative ring spectra

Definition 8.1.

[104, Definition 4.1.3] ‚Äâ Let A‚ÜíB‚Üíùê¥ùêµA\rightarrow B be a map of commutative ring spectra and let Gùê∫G be a finite group acting on BùêµB via commutative Aùê¥A-algebra maps. Assume that S‚ÜíA‚ÜíB‚ÜíùëÜùê¥‚ÜíùêµS\rightarrow A\rightarrow B is a sequence of cofibrations in the model structure on commutative ring spectra of [34, Corollary VII.4.10]. Then A‚ÜíB‚Üíùê¥ùêµA\rightarrow B is a Gùê∫G-Galois extension if

  1. (a)

    the canonical map Œπ:A‚ÜíBh‚ÄãG:ùúÑ‚Üíùê¥superscriptùêµ‚Ñéùê∫\iota\colon A\rightarrow B^{hG} is a weak equivalence and

  2. (b)
    (8.1) h:B‚àßAB‚Üí‚àèGB:‚Ñé‚Üísubscriptùê¥ùêµùêµsubscriptproductùê∫ùêµh\colon B\wedge_{A}B\rightarrow\prod_{G}B

    is a weak equivalence.

The first condition is the familiar fixed points condition from classical Galois theory of fields. The map ŒπùúÑ\iota comes from taking the adjoint of the map

where p:E‚ÄãG+‚ÜíS0:ùëù‚Üíùê∏subscriptùê∫superscriptùëÜ0p\colon EG_{+}\rightarrow S^{0} collapses E‚ÄãGùê∏ùê∫EG to the non-base point of S0superscriptùëÜ0S^{0}.

The map h‚Ñéh is adjoint to the composite

B‚àßAB‚àßG+‚ÜíB‚àßAB‚ÜíB‚Üísubscriptùê¥ùêµùêµsubscriptùê∫subscriptùê¥ùêµùêµ‚ÜíùêµB\wedge_{A}B\wedge G_{+}\rightarrow B\wedge_{A}B\rightarrow B

that comes from the Gùê∫G-action on the right factor of B‚àßABsubscriptùê¥ùêµùêµB\wedge_{A}B followed by the multiplication in BùêµB. (Informally, if smashes were tensors, then h‚Äã(b1‚äób2)=(b1‚ãÖg‚Äã(b2))g‚ààG‚Ñétensor-productsubscriptùëè1subscriptùëè2subscript‚ãÖsubscriptùëè1ùëîsubscriptùëè2ùëîùê∫h(b_{1}\otimes b_{2})=(b_{1}\cdot g(b_{2}))_{g\in G}.) Note that ‚àèGBsubscriptproductùê∫ùêµ\prod_{G}B is isomorphic to F‚Äã(G+,B)ùêπsubscriptùê∫ùêµF(G_{+},B), so we could rewrite the condition in (8.1) as the requirement that

h:B‚àßAB‚ÜíF‚Äã(G+,B):‚Ñé‚Üísubscriptùê¥ùêµùêµùêπsubscriptùê∫ùêµh\colon B\wedge_{A}B\rightarrow F(G_{+},B)

is a weak equivalence.

The condition that the map h‚Ñéh from (8.1) is a weak equivalence is crucial. It is also necessary for Galois extensions of discrete commutative rings in order to ensure that the extension is unramified. For instance ‚Ñ§‚äÇ‚Ñ§‚Äã[i]‚Ñ§‚Ñ§delimited-[]ùëñ\mathbb{Z}\subset\mathbb{Z}[i] satisfies that ‚Ñ§‚Äã[i]C2=‚Ñ§‚Ñ§superscriptdelimited-[]ùëñsubscriptùê∂2‚Ñ§\mathbb{Z}[i]^{C_{2}}=\mathbb{Z}, but h:‚Ñ§‚Äã[i]‚äó‚Ñ§‚Ñ§‚Äã[i]‚Üí‚Ñ§‚Äã[i]√ó‚Ñ§‚Äã[i]:‚Ñé‚Üísubscripttensor-product‚Ñ§‚Ñ§delimited-[]ùëñ‚Ñ§delimited-[]ùëñ‚Ñ§delimited-[]ùëñ‚Ñ§delimited-[]ùëñh\colon\mathbb{Z}[i]\otimes_{\mathbb{Z}}\mathbb{Z}[i]\rightarrow\mathbb{Z}[i]\times\mathbb{Z}[i] is not surjective: h‚Ñéh detects the ramification at the prime 222. Therefore ‚Ñ§‚Üí‚Ñ§‚Äã[i]‚Üí‚Ñ§‚Ñ§delimited-[]ùëñ\mathbb{Z}\rightarrow\mathbb{Z}[i] is not a C2subscriptùê∂2C_{2}-Galois extension but ‚Ñ§‚Äã[12]‚Üí‚Ñ§‚Äã[12,i]‚Üí‚Ñ§delimited-[]12‚Ñ§12ùëñ\mathbb{Z}[\frac{1}{2}]\rightarrow\mathbb{Z}[\frac{1}{2},i] is C2subscriptùê∂2C_{2}-Galois.

Galois extensions of commutative ring spectra can have rather bad properties as modules. So the following definition is actually an additional assumption (this does not happen in the discrete setting).

Definition 8.2.

[104, Definition 4.3.1] A Galois extension A‚ÜíB‚Üíùê¥ùêµA\rightarrow B is faithful if it is faithful as an Aùê¥A-module, i.e., for every Aùê¥A-module MùëÄM with M‚àßAB‚âÉ‚àósimilar-to-or-equalssubscriptùê¥ùëÄùêµM\wedge_{A}B\simeq* we have M‚âÉ‚àósimilar-to-or-equalsùëÄM\simeq*.

Important examples of Galois extensions of commutative ring spectra are the following. By Cnsubscriptùê∂ùëõC_{n} we denote the cyclic group of order nùëõn.

  1. (a)

    The concept of Galois extensions of commutative ring spectra corresponds to the one for commutative rings via the Eilenberg-Mac‚ÄâLane spectrum functor [104, Proposition 4.2]: Let R‚ÜíT‚ÜíùëÖùëáR\rightarrow T be a homomorphism of discrete commutative rings and let Gùê∫G be a finite group acting on TùëáT via RùëÖR-algebra homomorphisms. Then R‚ÜíT‚ÜíùëÖùëáR\rightarrow T is a Gùê∫G-Galois extension of commutative rings if and only if ùêªùëÖ‚ÜíH‚ÄãT‚ÜíùêªùëÖùêªùëá\mathit{HR}\rightarrow H\!T is a Gùê∫G-Galois extension of commutative ring spectra.

  2. (b)

    The complexification of real vector bundles gives rise to a map of commutative ring spectra ùêæùëÇ‚Üíùêæùëà‚ÜíùêæùëÇùêæùëà\mathit{KO}\rightarrow\mathit{KU} from real to complex topological K-theory. There is a C2subscriptùê∂2C_{2}-action on ùêæùëàùêæùëà\mathit{KU} corresponding to complex conjugation of complex vector bundles. Rognes shows [104, Proposition 5.3.1] that this turns ùêæùëÇ‚Üíùêæùëà‚ÜíùêæùëÇùêæùëà\mathit{KO}\rightarrow\mathit{KU} into a C2subscriptùê∂2C_{2}-Galois extension.

  3. (c)

    At an odd prime pùëùp there is a pùëùp-adic Adams operation on K‚ÄãUpùêæsubscriptùëàùëùKU_{p} that gives rise to a Cp‚àí1subscriptùê∂ùëù1C_{p-1}-action on K‚ÄãUpùêæsubscriptùëàùëùKU_{p} such that Lp‚ÜíK‚ÄãUp‚ÜísubscriptùêøùëùùêæsubscriptùëàùëùL_{p}\rightarrow KU_{p} is a Cp‚àí1subscriptùê∂ùëù1C_{p-1}-Galois extension (see [104, 5.5.4]).

  4. (d)

    There is a notion of pro-Galois extensions of commutative ring spectra and LK‚Äã(n)‚ÄãS‚ÜíEn‚ÜísubscriptùêøùêæùëõùëÜsubscriptùê∏ùëõL_{K(n)}S\rightarrow E_{n} is a K‚Äã(n)ùêæùëõK(n)-local pro-Galois extension with the extended Morava stabilizer group as the Galois group [104, Theorem 5.4.4].

  5. (e)

    Let pùëùp be an arbitrary prime. The projection map œÄ:E‚ÄãCp‚ÜíB‚ÄãCp:ùúã‚Üíùê∏subscriptùê∂ùëùùêµsubscriptùê∂ùëù\pi\colon EC_{p}\rightarrow BC_{p} induces a map on function spectra

    F‚Äã(œÄ+,H‚ÄãùîΩp):F‚Äã((B‚ÄãCp)+,H‚ÄãùîΩp)‚ÜíF‚Äã((E‚ÄãCp)+,H‚ÄãùîΩp)‚àºH‚ÄãùîΩp:ùêπsubscriptùúãùêªsubscriptùîΩùëù‚Üíùêπsubscriptùêµsubscriptùê∂ùëùùêªsubscriptùîΩùëùùêπsubscriptùê∏subscriptùê∂ùëùùêªsubscriptùîΩùëùsimilar-toùêªsubscriptùîΩùëùF(\pi_{+},H\mathbb{F}_{p})\colon F((BC_{p})_{+},H\mathbb{F}_{p})\rightarrow F((EC_{p})_{+},H\mathbb{F}_{p})\sim H\mathbb{F}_{p}

    which identifies H‚ÄãùîΩpùêªsubscriptùîΩùëùH\mathbb{F}_{p} as a Cpsubscriptùê∂ùëùC_{p}-Galois extension over F‚Äã((B‚ÄãCp)+,H‚ÄãùîΩp)ùêπsubscriptùêµsubscriptùê∂ùëùùêªsubscriptùîΩùëùF((BC_{p})_{+},H\mathbb{F}_{p}) [104, Proposition 5.6.3]. Hence in the world of commutative ring spectra group cohomology sits between SùëÜS and H‚ÄãùîΩpùêªsubscriptùîΩùëùH\mathbb{F}_{p} as the base of a Galois extension! Beware, this Galois extension is not faithful. This observation is due to Ben Wieland: the Tate construction H‚ÄãùîΩpt‚ÄãCpùêªsuperscriptsubscriptùîΩùëùùë°subscriptùê∂ùëùH\mathbb{F}_{p}^{tC_{p}} isn‚Äôt trivial and it is actually killed by the Galois extension (in the spectral sequence you augment a Laurent generator to zero).

  6. (f)

    Studying elliptic curves with level structures gives C2subscriptùê∂2C_{2}-Galois extensions ùñ≥ùñ¨ùñ•0‚Äã(3)‚Üíùñ≥ùñ¨ùñ•1‚Äã(3)‚Üísubscriptùñ≥ùñ¨ùñ•03subscriptùñ≥ùñ¨ùñ•13\mathsf{TMF}_{0}(3)\rightarrow\mathsf{TMF}_{1}(3) and ùñ≥ùóÜùñø0‚Äã(3)‚Üíùñ≥ùóÜùñø1‚Äã(3)‚Üísubscriptùñ≥ùóÜùñø03subscriptùñ≥ùóÜùñø13\mathsf{Tmf}_{0}(3)\rightarrow\mathsf{Tmf}_{1}(3) [78, Theorems 7.6, 7.12]. For ùñ≥ùñ¨ùñ•1‚Äã(3)subscriptùñ≥ùñ¨ùñ•13\mathsf{TMF}_{1}(3) (and ùñ≥ùóÜùñø1‚Äã(3)subscriptùñ≥ùóÜùñø13\mathsf{Tmf}_{1}(3)) you consider elliptic curves with one chosen point of exact order 333 and for ùñ≥ùñ¨ùñ•0‚Äã(3)subscriptùñ≥ùñ¨ùñ•03\mathsf{TMF}_{0}(3) (and ùñ≥ùóÜùñø0‚Äã(3)subscriptùñ≥ùóÜùñø03\mathsf{Tmf}_{0}(3)) you only remember a subgroup of order 333. As C2‚âÖ‚Ñ§/3‚Äã‚Ñ§√ósubscriptùê∂2‚Ñ§3superscript‚Ñ§C_{2}\cong\mathbb{Z}/3\mathbb{Z}^{\times} this gives a C2subscriptùê∂2C_{2}-action. This can be made rigorous (see [47, 46, 78]).

8.2. Notions of √©tale morphisms

Weibel-Geller [123] show that for an √©tale extension of commutative rings œÜ:A‚ÜíB:ùúë‚Üíùê¥ùêµ\varphi\colon A\rightarrow B Hochschild homology satisfies √©tale descent: The map ùñßùñß‚Äã(œÜ)‚àóùñßùñßsubscriptùúë\mathsf{HH}(\varphi)_{*} induces an isomorphism

(8.3) ùñßùñß‚àó‚Äã(A)‚âÖùñßùñß‚àó‚Äã(B)Gsubscriptùñßùñßùê¥subscriptùñßùñßsuperscriptùêµùê∫\mathsf{HH}_{*}(A)\cong\mathsf{HH}_{*}(B)^{G}

In addition to having the right fixed-point property it satisfies

ùñßùñß‚àó‚Äã(B)‚äóùñßùñß‚àó‚Äã(A)ùñßùñß‚àó‚Äã(B)subscripttensor-productsubscriptùñßùñßùê¥subscriptùñßùñßùêµsubscriptùñßùñßùêµ\displaystyle\mathsf{HH}_{*}(B)\otimes_{\mathsf{HH}_{*}(A)}\mathsf{HH}_{*}(B) ‚âÖB‚äóAùñßùñß‚àó‚Äã(A)‚äóùñßùñß‚àó‚Äã(A)B‚äóAùñßùñß‚àó‚Äã(A)absentsubscripttensor-productùê¥subscripttensor-productsubscriptùñßùñßùê¥subscripttensor-productùê¥ùêµsubscriptùñßùñßùê¥ùêµsubscriptùñßùñßùê¥\displaystyle\cong B\otimes_{A}\mathsf{HH}_{*}(A)\otimes_{\mathsf{HH}_{*}(A)}B\otimes_{A}\mathsf{HH}_{*}(A)
‚âÖB‚äóAB‚äóAùñßùñß‚àó‚Äã(A)absentsubscripttensor-productùê¥subscripttensor-productùê¥ùêµùêµsubscriptùñßùñßùê¥\displaystyle\cong B\otimes_{A}B\otimes_{A}\mathsf{HH}_{*}(A)

If œÜ:A‚ÜíB:ùúë‚Üíùê¥ùêµ\varphi\colon A\rightarrow B is √©tale, then the module of K√§hler differentials Œ©B|A1subscriptsuperscriptŒ©1conditionalùêµùê¥\Omega^{1}_{B|A} is trivial and it can be easily seen that the map B‚Üíùñßùñß‚àóA‚Äã(B)‚Üíùêµsubscriptsuperscriptùñßùñßùê¥ùêµB\rightarrow\mathsf{HH}^{A}_{*}(B) is an isomorphism and that Andr√©-Quillen homology of BùêµB over Aùê¥A is trivial, because √©tale algebras are smooth.

For commutative ring spectra the situation is different. There are several non-equivalent notions of √©tale maps:

Definition 8.3.

Let œÜ:A‚ÜíB:ùúë‚Üíùê¥ùêµ\varphi\colon A\rightarrow B be a morphism of commutative ring spectra.

  1. (a)

    [69, Definition 7.5.1.4] We call œÜùúë\varphi Lurie-√©tale, if œÄ0‚Äã(œÜ):œÄ0‚Äã(A)‚ÜíœÄ0‚Äã(B):subscriptùúã0ùúë‚Üísubscriptùúã0ùê¥subscriptùúã0ùêµ\pi_{0}(\varphi)\colon\pi_{0}(A)\rightarrow\pi_{0}(B) is an √©tale map of commutative rings and if the canonical map

    œÄ‚àó‚Äã(A)‚äóœÄ0‚Äã(A)œÄ0‚Äã(B)‚ÜíœÄ‚àó‚Äã(B)‚Üísubscripttensor-productsubscriptùúã0ùê¥subscriptùúãùê¥subscriptùúã0ùêµsubscriptùúãùêµ\pi_{*}(A)\otimes_{\pi_{0}(A)}\pi_{0}(B)\rightarrow\pi_{*}(B)

    is an isomorphism.

  2. (b)

    [85, Definiton 3.2], [104, Definition 9.2.1] The morphism œÜùúë\varphi is (formally) ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH}-√©tale, if B‚Üíùñ≥ùñßùñßA‚Äã(B)‚Üíùêµsuperscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßùê¥ùêµB\rightarrow\mathsf{THH}^{A}(B) is a weak equivalence.

  3. (c)

    [85, Definiton 3.2], [104, Definition 9.4.1] We define œÜùúë\varphi to be (formally) ùñ≥ùñ†ùñ∞ùñ≥ùñ†ùñ∞\mathsf{TAQ}-√©tale, if ùñ≥ùñ†ùñ∞‚Äã(B|A)ùñ≥ùñ†ùñ∞conditionalùêµùê¥\mathsf{TAQ}(B|A) is weakly equivalent to ‚àó‚àó\ast.

Remark 8.4.
  • ‚Ä¢

    Rognes [104] reserves the labels ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH}-√©tale and ùñ≥ùñ†ùñ∞ùñ≥ùñ†ùñ∞\mathsf{TAQ}-√©tale only for such maps that ‚Äì in addition to the conditions above ‚Äì identify BùêµB as a dualizable Aùê¥A-module.

  • ‚Ä¢

    The condition of being Lurie-√©tale is strong and is a very algebraic one. It is for instance not satisfied by the C2subscriptùê∂2C_{2}-Galois extension ùêæùëÇ‚Üíùêæùëà‚ÜíùêæùëÇùêæùëà\mathit{KO}\rightarrow\mathit{KU} because on the level of homotopy groups this extension is rather appalling, compare (1.1).

  • ‚Ä¢

    McCarthy and Minasian show that ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH}-√©tale implies ùñ≥ùñ†ùñ∞ùñ≥ùñ†ùñ∞\mathsf{TAQ}-√©tale and they show that for n>1ùëõ1n>1 the map H‚ÄãùîΩp‚ÜíF‚Äã(K‚Äã(‚Ñ§/p‚Äã‚Ñ§,n)+,H‚ÄãùîΩp)‚ÜíùêªsubscriptùîΩùëùùêπùêæsubscript‚Ñ§ùëù‚Ñ§ùëõùêªsubscriptùîΩùëùH\mathbb{F}_{p}\rightarrow F(K(\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z},n)_{+},H\mathbb{F}_{p}) is a ùñ≥ùñ†ùñ∞ùñ≥ùñ†ùñ∞\mathsf{TAQ}-√©tale morphism that is not ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH}-√©tale. They attribute this example to Mike Mandell [85, Example 3.5]. Minasian [89, Corollary 2.8] proves that both notions are equivalent for morphisms between connective commutative ring spectra.

  • ‚Ä¢

    For connective spectra, the notion of Lurie-√©taleness has several good features [69, ¬ß7.5] and Mathew shows in [77, Corollary 3.1] that one can use [68, Lemma 8.9] to show that under some finiteness condition ùñ≥ùñ†ùñ∞ùñ≥ùñ†ùñ∞\mathsf{TAQ}-√©taleness implies Lurie-√©taleness in the connective case.

Definition 8.5.

[104, Definition 9.1.1] Let Cùê∂C be a cofibrant associative Aùê¥A-algebra spectrum. Then Cùê∂C is separable if the multiplication map Œº:C‚àßACo‚ÜíC:ùúá‚Üísubscriptùê¥ùê∂superscriptùê∂ùëúùê∂\mu\colon C\wedge_{A}C^{o}\rightarrow C has a section in the homotopy category of Cùê∂C-bimodule spectra.

Proposition 8.6.

[104, 9.2.6] ‚Äâ If Cùê∂C is a commutative separable Aùê¥A-algebra spectrum, then Cùê∂C is ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH}-√©tale.

is the identity. In addition, we get a splitting in the homotopy category of Cùê∂C-bimodule spectra,

i.e., the above composite is the identity on Cùê∂C. Taking the derived smash product C‚àßC‚àßACL(‚àí)subscriptsuperscriptùêøsubscriptùê¥ùê∂ùê∂ùê∂C\wedge^{L}_{C\wedge_{A}C}(-) of the above sequence gives the sequence

Definition 8.7.

Let A‚ÜíB‚Üíùê¥ùêµA\rightarrow B be a map of commutative ring spectra and let Gùê∫G be a finite group acting on BùêµB via maps of commutative Aùê¥A-algebra spectra. Proposition 8.8.

(compare [104, Lemma 9.1.2]) ‚Äâ If A‚ÜíB‚Üíùê¥ùêµA\rightarrow B is unramified, then BùêµB is separable over Aùê¥A.

Proof.

The canonical inclusion map i:B‚ÜíF‚Äã(G+,B):ùëñ‚Üíùêµùêπsubscriptùê∫ùêµi\colon B\rightarrow F(G_{+},B) can be modelled by the pointed map from G+subscriptùê∫G_{+} to S0superscriptùëÜ0S^{0}, that sends the neutral element e‚ààGùëíùê∫e\in G to the non-basepoint of S0superscriptùëÜ0S^{0} and sends all other elements to the basepoint. Note that h‚Ñéh is not a BùêµB-bimodule map, but we are only interested in its eùëíe-component of F‚Äã(G+,B)ùêπsubscriptùê∫ùêµF(G_{+},B). ‚àé

Thus we can conclude that unramified maps of commutative ring spectra are ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH}-√©tale and that the failure of the map B‚Üíùñ≥ùñßùñßA‚Äã(B)‚Üíùêµsuperscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßùê¥ùêµB\rightarrow\mathsf{THH}^{A}(B) to being a weak equivalence detects ramification. This idea was exploited in [33] in order to identify for instance k‚Äão‚Üík‚Äãu‚Üíùëòùëúùëòùë¢ko\rightarrow ku as a wildly ramified extension whereas the inclusion of the Adams summand ‚Ñì‚Üík‚Äãu(p)‚Üí‚Ñìùëòsubscriptùë¢ùëù\ell\rightarrow ku_{(p)} is tamely ramified [33, Theorems 4.1, 5.2]. Sagave also identified this map as being log-√©tale [106, Theorem 1.6].

8.3. Versions of √©tale descent

Transferring the Geller-Weibel result to the setting of commutative ring spectra, it seems natural to define two versions of descent:

Definition 8.9.

In the following œÜ:A‚ÜíB:ùúë‚Üíùê¥ùêµ\varphi\colon A\rightarrow B is a cofibration and Aùê¥A is cofibrant.

  • ‚Ä¢

    The morphism œÜ:A‚ÜíB:ùúë‚Üíùê¥ùêµ\varphi\colon A\rightarrow B satisfies √©tale descent if the canonical morphism

    (8.4) B‚àßAùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(A)‚Üíùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(B)‚Üísubscriptùê¥ùêµùñ≥ùñßùñßùê¥ùñ≥ùñßùñßùêµB\wedge_{A}\mathsf{THH}(A)\rightarrow\mathsf{THH}(B)

    is a weak equivalence.

  • ‚Ä¢

    If œÜ:A‚ÜíB:ùúë‚Üíùê¥ùêµ\varphi\colon A\rightarrow B is a map of commutative ring spectra and if Gùê∫G is a finite group acting on BùêµB via commutative Aùê¥A-algebra maps, then we say that œÜùúë\varphi satisfies Galois descent if the map

    (8.5) ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(A)‚Üíùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(B)h‚ÄãG‚Üíùñ≥ùñßùñßùê¥ùñ≥ùñßùñßsuperscriptùêµ‚Ñéùê∫\mathsf{THH}(A)\rightarrow\mathsf{THH}(B)^{hG}

    is a weak equivalence.

Akhil Mathew clarifies the relationship between the different notions of √©tale morphisms and the notions of descent. He proves that Lurie-√©tale morphisms satisfy √©tale descent [77, Theorem 1.3] and he shows that for a faithful Gùê∫G-Galois extension with finite Galois group Gùê∫G, both descent properties are equivalent [77, Proposition 4.3] and they are in turn equivalent to the property that ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(A)‚Üíùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(B)‚Üíùñ≥ùñßùñßùê¥ùñ≥ùñßùñßùêµ\mathsf{THH}(A)\rightarrow\mathsf{THH}(B) is again a Gùê∫G-Galois extension.

Moreover, he shows that the morphism

œÜ:F‚Äã(ùïä+1,H‚ÄãùîΩp)‚ÜíF‚Äã(ùïä+1,H‚ÄãùîΩp):ùúë‚Üíùêπsubscriptsuperscriptùïä1ùêªsubscriptùîΩùëùùêπsubscriptsuperscriptùïä1ùêªsubscriptùîΩùëù\varphi\colon F(\mathbb{S}^{1}_{+},H\mathbb{F}_{p})\rightarrow F(\mathbb{S}^{1}_{+},H\mathbb{F}_{p})

that is induced by the degree-pùëùp map on ùïä1superscriptùïä1\mathbb{S}^{1} is a faithful Cpsubscriptùê∂ùëùC_{p}-Galois extension, but that it does not satisfy √©tale descent [77, Theorem 2.1] and hence it doesn‚Äôt satisfy Galois descent.

The Hopf fibration ùïä1‚Üíùïä3‚Üíùïä2‚Üísuperscriptùïä1superscriptùïä3‚Üísuperscriptùïä2\mathbb{S}^{1}\rightarrow\mathbb{S}^{3}\rightarrow\mathbb{S}^{2} is a principal ùïä1superscriptùïä1\mathbb{S}^{1}-bundle. The corresponding morphism of commutative H‚Äã‚Ñöùêª‚ÑöH\mathbb{Q}-algebra spectra of cochains

F‚Äã(Œ∑,H‚Äã‚Ñö):F‚Äã(ùïä+2,H‚Äã‚Ñö)‚ÜíF‚Äã(ùïä+3,H‚Äã‚Ñö):ùêπùúÇùêª‚Ñö‚Üíùêπsubscriptsuperscriptùïä2ùêª‚Ñöùêπsubscriptsuperscriptùïä3ùêª‚ÑöF(\eta,H\mathbb{Q})\colon F(\mathbb{S}^{2}_{+},H\mathbb{Q})\rightarrow F(\mathbb{S}^{3}_{+},H\mathbb{Q})

is therefore an ùïä1superscriptùïä1\mathbb{S}^{1}-Galois extension [104, Proposition 5.6.3].

In joint work with Christian Ausoni we show that the morphism F‚Äã(Œ∑,H‚Äã‚Ñö)ùêπùúÇùêª‚ÑöF(\eta,H\mathbb{Q}) does not satisfy Galois descent, i.e.,

ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(F‚Äã(ùïä+2,H‚Äã‚Ñö))‚âÅùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(F‚Äã(ùïä+3,H‚Äã‚Ñö))h‚Äãùïä1::not-similar-toùñ≥ùñßùñßùêπsubscriptsuperscriptùïä2ùêª‚Ñöùñ≥ùñßùñßsuperscriptùêπsubscriptsuperscriptùïä3ùêª‚Ñö‚Ñésuperscriptùïä1absent\mathsf{THH}(F(\mathbb{S}^{2}_{+},H\mathbb{Q}))\nsim\mathsf{THH}(F(\mathbb{S}^{3}_{+},H\mathbb{Q}))^{h\mathbb{S}^{1}}:

The homotopy groups of ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(F‚Äã(ùïä+2,H‚Äã‚Ñö))ùñ≥ùñßùñßùêπsubscriptsuperscriptùïä2ùêª‚Ñö\mathsf{THH}(F(\mathbb{S}^{2}_{+},H\mathbb{Q})) contain an element in degree ‚àí11-1 that is not present in œÄ‚àó‚Äã(ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(F‚Äã(ùïä+3,H‚Äã‚Ñö))h‚Äãùïä1)subscriptùúãùñ≥ùñßùñßsuperscriptùêπsubscriptsuperscriptùïä3ùêª‚Ñö‚Ñésuperscriptùïä1\pi_{*}(\mathsf{THH}(F(\mathbb{S}^{3}_{+},H\mathbb{Q}))^{h\mathbb{S}^{1}}).

Mathew identifies the problem with √©tale descent of finite faithful Galois extensions for ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH} as being caused by the non-trivial fundamental group of ùïä1superscriptùïä1\mathbb{S}^{1}. He shows the following result.

Theorem 8.10.

[77, Proposition 5.2] ‚Äâ Let XùëãX be a simply connected pointed space and let A‚ÜíB‚Üíùê¥ùêµA\rightarrow B be a faithful Gùê∫G-Galois extension of commutative ring spectra with finite Gùê∫G. Then the map

B‚àßA(X‚äóA)‚ÜíX‚äóB‚Üísubscriptùê¥ùêµtensor-productùëãùê¥tensor-productùëãùêµB\wedge_{A}(X\otimes A)\rightarrow X\otimes B

is a weak equivalence.

In particular, higher order topological Hochschild homology, ùñ≥ùñßùñß[n]superscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßdelimited-[]ùëõ\mathsf{THH}^{[n]} for n‚©æ2ùëõ2n\geqslant 2, does satisfy √©tale descent for faithful finite Galois extensions. However, √©tale descent remains for instance an issue for torus homology.

Note that sometimes ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH} does satisfy descent, even for ramified maps of commutative ring spectra. For instance, Christian Ausoni shows in [9, Theorem 10.2] that ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(‚Ñìp)ùñ≥ùñßùñßsubscript‚Ñìùëù\mathsf{THH}(\ell_{p}) is pùëùp-adically equivalent to ùñ≥ùñßùñß‚Äã(k‚Äãup)h‚ÄãCp‚àí1ùñ≥ùñßùñßsuperscriptùëòsubscriptùë¢ùëù‚Ñésubscriptùê∂ùëù1\mathsf{THH}(ku_{p})^{hC_{p-1}} and even that K‚Äã(‚Ñìp)ùêæsubscript‚ÑìùëùK(\ell_{p}) is pùëùp-adically equivalent to K‚Äã(k‚Äãup)h‚ÄãCp‚àí1ùêæsuperscriptùëòsubscriptùë¢ùëù‚Ñésubscriptùê∂ùëù1K(ku_{p})^{hC_{p-1}}.

Remark 8.11.

In [30] Clausen, Mathew, Naumann and Noel prove far-reaching Galois descent results for topological Hochschild homology and algebraic K-theory; in particular they confirm a Galois descent conjecture for algebraic K-theory by Ausoni and Rognes in many important cases. They identify ùñ≥ùñßùñßùñ≥ùñßùñß\mathsf{THH} as a weakly additive invariant (see [30, Definition 3.11]) and prove descent in the form of [30, Theorems 5.1,5.6].

9. Picard and Brauer groups

9.1. Picard groups in the setting of a symmetric monoidal category

Let (ùíû,‚äó,1,œÑ)ùíûtensor-product1ùúè(\mathcal{C},\otimes,1,\tau) be a symmetric monoidal category. An important class of objects in ùíûùíû\mathcal{C} are those objects Cùê∂C that have an inverse with respect to ‚äótensor-product\otimes, i.e., there is an object C‚Ä≤superscriptùê∂‚Ä≤C^{\prime} of ùíûùíû\mathcal{C} such that

C‚äóC‚Ä≤‚âÖ1.tensor-productùê∂superscriptùê∂‚Ä≤1C\otimes C^{\prime}\cong 1.

One wants to gather such objects in a category and build a space and spectrum out of them:

Definition 9.1.

The Picard groupoid of ùíûùíû\mathcal{C}, ùñØùóÇùñºùñ∫ùóãùñΩ‚Äã(ùíû)ùñØùóÇùñºùñ∫ùóãùñΩùíû\mathsf{Picard}(\mathcal{C}), is the category whose objects are the invertible objects of ùíûùíû\mathcal{C} and whose morphisms are isomorphisms between invertible objects.

In general, this category might not be small. Note that if C1subscriptùê∂1C_{1} and C2subscriptùê∂2C_{2} are objects of ùñØùóÇùñºùñ∫ùóãùñΩ‚Äã(ùíû)ùñØùóÇùñºùñ∫ùóãùñΩùíû\mathsf{Picard}(\mathcal{C}), then so is C1‚äóC2tensor-productsubscriptùê∂1subscriptùê∂2C_{1}\otimes C_{2}; in fact, ùñØùóÇùñºùñ∫ùóãùñΩ‚Äã(ùíû)ùñØùóÇùñºùñ∫ùóãùñΩùíû\mathsf{Picard}(\mathcal{C}) is itself a symmetric monoidal category.

Definition 9.2.

Let ùíûùíû\mathcal{C} be as above and assume that ùñØùóÇùñºùñ∫ùóãùñΩ‚Äã(ùíû)ùñØùóÇùñºùñ∫ùóãùñΩùíû\mathsf{Picard}(\mathcal{C}) is small.

Then ùñØùñ®ùñ¢‚Äã(ùíû)ùñØùñ®ùñ¢ùíû\mathsf{PIC}(\mathcal{C}) is the classifying space of the symmetric monoidal category ùñØùóÇùñºùñ∫ùóãùñΩ‚Äã(ùíû)ùñØùóÇùñºùñ∫ùóãùñΩùíû\mathsf{Picard}(\mathcal{C}) and let ùóâùóÇùñº‚Äã(ùíû)ùóâùóÇùñºùíû\mathsf{pic}(\mathcal{C}) denote the connective spectrum associated to the infinite loop space associated to ùñØùñ®ùñ¢‚Äã(ùíû)ùñØùñ®ùñ¢ùíû\mathsf{PIC}(\mathcal{C}).

The Picard group of ùíûùíû\mathcal{C}, ùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(ùíû)ùñØùóÇùñºùíû\mathsf{Pic}(\mathcal{C}), is œÄ0‚ÄãùñØùñ®ùñ¢‚Äã(ùíû)subscriptùúã0ùñØùñ®ùñ¢ùíû\pi_{0}\mathsf{PIC}(\mathcal{C}).

If the Picard groupoid of ùíûùíû\mathcal{C} is small, then the Picard group can also be described as the set of isomorphism classes of invertible objects of ùíûùíû\mathcal{C} with the product

[C1]‚äó[C2]:=[C1‚äóC2].assigntensor-productdelimited-[]subscriptùê∂1delimited-[]subscriptùê∂2delimited-[]tensor-productsubscriptùê∂1subscriptùê∂2[C_{1}]\otimes[C_{2}]:=[C_{1}\otimes C_{2}].

The neutral element is the isomorphism class of the unit, [1]delimited-[]1[1].

Definition 9.3.

Let RùëÖR be a (discrete) commutative ring, then we denote by ùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(R)ùñØùóÇùñºùëÖ\mathsf{Pic}(R) the Picard group of the symmetric monoidal category of the category of RùëÖR-modules and by ùñØùñ®ùñ¢‚Äã(R)ùñØùñ®ùñ¢ùëÖ\mathsf{PIC}(R) (and ùóâùóÇùñº‚Äã(R)ùóâùóÇùñºùëÖ\mathsf{pic}(R)) the Picard space (and Picard spectrum) of this category.

For instance the Picard group of a ring of integers in a number ring is its ideal class group.

9.2. Picard group for commutative ring spectra

For commutative ring spectra RùëÖR, the above definition of ùñØùñ®ùñ¢‚Äã(R)ùñØùñ®ùñ¢ùëÖ\mathsf{PIC}(R) and ùóâùóÇùñº‚Äã(R)ùóâùóÇùñºùëÖ\mathsf{pic}(R) would either be much too rigid (if one would choose ùíûùíû\mathcal{C} to be the category of RùëÖR-module spectra and isomorphisms) or not strict enough (if one would take ùíûùíû\mathcal{C} to be the homotopy category of RùëÖR-module spectra). See [80, ¬ß2] for an adequate background for a suitable definition and see [36, ¬ß4] for a dictionary how to pass from a commutative ring spectrum RùëÖR and its category of modules to the ‚àû\infty-categorical setting. Instead of working with symmetric monoidal categories, one uses presentable symmetric monoidal ‚àû\infty-categories ùíûùíû\mathcal{C}. Then the Picard ‚àû\infty-groupoid of ùíûùíû\mathcal{C} is the maximal subgroupoid of the underlying ‚àû\infty-category of ùíûùíû\mathcal{C} spanned by the invertible objects. This groupoid is equivalent to a grouplike E‚àûsubscriptùê∏E_{\infty}-space ùñØùñ®ùñ¢‚Äã(ùíû)ùñØùñ®ùñ¢ùíû\mathsf{PIC}(\mathcal{C}) and hence there is a connective ring spectrum, ùóâùóÇùñº‚Äã(ùíû)ùóâùóÇùñºùíû\mathsf{pic}(\mathcal{C}), associated to ùíûùíû\mathcal{C} [36, ¬ß5].

Let RùëÖR be a commutative ring spectrum. The operadic nerve of the category of cofibrant-fibrant RùëÖR-modules is a stable presentable symmetric monoidal ‚àû\infty-category [69, Proposition 4.1.3.10] and we will abbreviate this as the ‚àû\infty-category of RùëÖR-modules, R‚ÄãmodùëÖmodR\text{mod}.

Definition 9.4.

The Picard group of a commutative ring spectrum RùëÖR, ùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(R)ùñØùóÇùñºùëÖ\mathsf{Pic}(R), is the group œÄ0‚Äã(ùñØùñ®ùñ¢‚Äã(R‚Äãmod))subscriptùúã0ùñØùñ®ùñ¢ùëÖmod\pi_{0}(\mathsf{PIC}(R\text{mod})).

Again, these Picard groups can also be described as the set of isomorphism classes of invertible RùëÖR-modules in the homotopy category of RùëÖR-module spectra.

The Picard space ùñØùñ®ùñ¢‚Äã(R)ùñØùñ®ùñ¢ùëÖ\mathsf{PIC}(R) is a delooping of the units of RùëÖR ([80, ¬ß2.2], [119, ¬ß5]): There is an equivalence

ùñØùñ®ùñ¢‚Äã(R)‚âÉùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(R)√óB‚ÄãG‚ÄãL1‚Äã(R).similar-to-or-equalsùñØùñ®ùñ¢ùëÖùñØùóÇùñºùëÖùêµùê∫subscriptùêø1ùëÖ\mathsf{PIC}(R)\simeq\mathsf{Pic}(R)\times BGL_{1}(R).
Remark 9.5.

There is a map ùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(œÄ‚àó‚ÄãR)‚ÜíùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(R)‚ÜíùñØùóÇùñºsubscriptùúãùëÖùñØùóÇùñºùëÖ\mathsf{Pic}(\pi_{*}R)\rightarrow\mathsf{Pic}(R) that realizes an element in the algebraic Picard group of invertible graded œÄ‚àó‚ÄãRsubscriptùúãùëÖ\pi_{*}R-modules as a module over RùëÖR and in many cases this map is actually an isomorphism [13, Theorem 43]. In this case we call ùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(R)ùñØùóÇùñºùëÖ\mathsf{Pic}(R) algebraic. A notable exception comes from Galois extensions of ring spectra: As in algebra, if A‚ÜíB‚Üíùê¥ùêµA\rightarrow B is a Gùê∫G-Galois extension of commutative ring spectra with abelian Galois group Gùê∫G, then [B]‚ààùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(A‚Äã[G])delimited-[]ùêµùñØùóÇùñºùê¥delimited-[]ùê∫[B]\in\mathsf{Pic}(A[G]) [104, Proposition 6.5.2]. But for instance [K‚ÄãU‚àó]delimited-[]ùêæsubscriptùëà[KU_{*}] is certainly not an element in the algebraic Picard group ùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(K‚ÄãO‚àó‚Äã[C2])ùñØùóÇùñºùêæsubscriptùëÇdelimited-[]subscriptùê∂2\mathsf{Pic}(KO_{*}[C_{2}]), see (1.1).

The equivalence classes of suspensions of RùëÖR are always in ùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(R)ùñØùóÇùñºùëÖ\mathsf{Pic}(R), but if RùëÖR is periodic, these suspensions don‚Äôt generate a free abelian group. Let us mention some crucial examples of Picard groups of commutative ring spectra:

  • ‚Ä¢

    The Picard group of the initial commutative ring spectrum SùëÜS is ùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(S)‚âÖ‚Ñ§ùñØùóÇùñºùëÜ‚Ñ§\mathsf{Pic}(S)\cong\mathbb{Z} where n‚àà‚Ñ§ùëõ‚Ñ§n\in\mathbb{Z} corresponds to the class of SnsuperscriptùëÜùëõS^{n} [51].

  • ‚Ä¢

    For connective commutative ring spectra the Picard group of RùëÖR is algebraic [13, Theorem 21], [80, Theorem 2.4.4].

  • ‚Ä¢

    For periodic real and complex K-theory the Picard groups just notices the suspensions of the ground ring: The Picard group of K‚ÄãUùêæùëàKU is algebraic: ùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(ùêæùëà)‚âÖ‚Ñ§/2‚Äã‚Ñ§ùñØùóÇùñºùêæùëà‚Ñ§2‚Ñ§\mathsf{Pic}(\mathit{KU})\cong\mathbb{Z}/2\mathbb{Z}, and ùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(ùêæùëÇ)‚âÖ‚Ñ§/8‚Äã‚Ñ§ùñØùóÇùñºùêæùëÇ‚Ñ§8‚Ñ§\mathsf{Pic}(\mathit{KO})\cong\mathbb{Z}/8\mathbb{Z} (Hopkins, [80, Example 7.1.1] and [36, ¬ß7]).

  • ‚Ä¢

    The same applies to the periodic verison of the spectrum of topological modular forms: ùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(ùñ≥ùñ¨ùñ•)‚âÖ‚Ñ§/576‚Äã‚Ñ§ùñØùóÇùñºùñ≥ùñ¨ùñ•‚Ñ§576‚Ñ§\mathsf{Pic}(\mathsf{TMF})\cong\mathbb{Z}/576\mathbb{Z} [80, Theorem A]. But for ùñ≥ùóÜùñøùñ≥ùóÜùñø\mathsf{Tmf}, the spectrum of topological forms that mediates between ùñ≥ùñ¨ùñ•ùñ≥ùñ¨ùñ•\mathsf{TMF} and its connective version ùóçùóÜùñøùóçùóÜùñø\mathsf{tmf} one gets [80, Theorem B]

    ùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(ùñ≥ùóÜùñø)‚âÖ‚Ñ§‚äï‚Ñ§/24‚Äã‚Ñ§ùñØùóÇùñºùñ≥ùóÜùñødirect-sum‚Ñ§‚Ñ§24‚Ñ§\mathsf{Pic}(\mathsf{Tmf})\cong\mathbb{Z}\oplus\mathbb{Z}/24\mathbb{Z}

    where the copy of the integers comes from the suspensions of ùñ≥ùóÜùñøùñ≥ùóÜùñø\mathsf{Tmf} and the generator of the ‚Ñ§/24‚Äã‚Ñ§‚Ñ§24‚Ñ§\mathbb{Z}/24\mathbb{Z}-summand is described in [80, Construction 8.4.2]

  • ‚Ä¢

    For any odd prime and any finite subgroup Gùê∫G of the full Morava stabilizer group ùîæp‚àí1subscriptùîæùëù1\mathbb{G}_{p-1} Heard, Mathew and Stojanoska [44, Theorem 1.5] prove ‚Äì using Galois descent techniques for ùóâùóÇùñºùóâùóÇùñº\mathsf{pic} ‚Äì that the Picard group of Ep‚àí1h‚ÄãGsuperscriptsubscriptùê∏ùëù1‚Ñéùê∫E_{p-1}^{hG} is a cyclic group generated by the suspension of Ep‚àí1h‚ÄãGsuperscriptsubscriptùê∏ùëù1‚Ñéùê∫E_{p-1}^{hG}.

A Picard group that contains more elements than just the ones coming from suspensions of the commutative ring spectrum says that there are more self-equivalences of the homotopy category of RùëÖR-modules than the standard suspensions. One might view this as twisted suspensions. Gepner and Lawson explore the concept of having a Picard-grading on the category of RùëÖR-module spectra and they develop a Pic-resolution model category structure in the sense of Bousfield [36, ¬ß3.2].

9.3. Descent method and local versions

A crucial method for calculating Picard groups is Galois descent. If A‚ÜíB‚Üíùê¥ùêµA\rightarrow B is a Gùê∫G-Galois extension (for Gùê∫G finite), then for the Picard spectra and spaces the following equivalences hold [36, 80]:

(9.1) ùóâùóÇùñº‚Äã(A)‚âÉœÑ‚©æ0‚ÄãùóâùóÇùñº‚Äã(B)h‚ÄãG‚Äã¬†and¬†‚ÄãùñØùñ®ùñ¢‚Äã(A)‚âÉùñØùñ®ùñ¢‚Äã(B)h‚ÄãG.similar-to-or-equalsùóâùóÇùñºùê¥subscriptùúèabsent0ùóâùóÇùñºsuperscriptùêµ‚Ñéùê∫¬†and¬†ùñØùñ®ùñ¢ùê¥similar-to-or-equalsùñØùñ®ùñ¢superscriptùêµ‚Ñéùê∫\mathsf{pic}(A)\simeq\tau_{\geqslant 0}\mathsf{pic}(B)^{hG}\text{ and }\mathsf{PIC}(A)\simeq\mathsf{PIC}(B)^{hG}.

Here, œÑ‚©æ0subscriptùúèabsent0\tau_{\geqslant 0} denotes the connective cover of a spectrum. In general, the extension BùêµB is easier to understand than Aùê¥A, for instance in the case of the C2subscriptùê∂2C_{2}-Galois extension ùêæùëÇ‚Üíùêæùëà‚ÜíùêæùëÇùêæùëà\mathit{KO}\rightarrow\mathit{KU}, one obtains information about ùóâùóÇùñº‚Äã(A)ùóâùóÇùñºùê¥\mathsf{pic}(A) using the homotopy fixed point spectral sequence

H‚àís‚Äã(G;œÄt‚ÄãùóâùóÇùñº‚Äã(B))‚áíœÄt‚àís‚Äã(ùóâùóÇùñº‚Äã(B)h‚ÄãG).‚áísuperscriptùêªùë†ùê∫subscriptùúãùë°ùóâùóÇùñºùêµsubscriptùúãùë°ùë†ùóâùóÇùñºsuperscriptùêµ‚Ñéùê∫H^{-s}(G;\pi_{t}\mathsf{pic}(B))\Rightarrow\pi_{t-s}(\mathsf{pic}(B)^{hG}).

In [47, ¬ß6] for instance, Hill and Meier use Galois descent to determine the Picard groups of ùñ≥ùñ¨ùñ•0‚Äã(3)subscriptùñ≥ùñ¨ùñ•03\mathsf{TMF}_{0}(3) and ùñ≥ùóÜùñø0‚Äã(3)subscriptùñ≥ùóÜùñø03\mathsf{Tmf}_{0}(3):

Theorem 9.6.

[47, Theorems 6.9, 6.12]

ùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(ùñ≥ùñ¨ùñ•0‚Äã(3))‚âÖ‚Ñ§/48‚Äã‚Ñ§‚Äã¬†and¬†‚ÄãùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(ùñ≥ùóÜùñø0‚Äã(3))‚âÖ‚Ñ§‚äï‚Ñ§/8‚Äã‚Ñ§.ùñØùóÇùñºsubscriptùñ≥ùñ¨ùñ•03‚Ñ§48‚Ñ§¬†and¬†ùñØùóÇùñºsubscriptùñ≥ùóÜùñø03direct-sum‚Ñ§‚Ñ§8‚Ñ§\mathsf{Pic}(\mathsf{TMF}_{0}(3))\cong\mathbb{Z}/48\mathbb{Z}\text{ and }\mathsf{Pic}(\mathsf{Tmf}_{0}(3))\cong\mathbb{Z}\oplus\mathbb{Z}/8\mathbb{Z}.

Hopkins-Mahowald-Sadofsky started the investigation of the Picard groups of the K‚Äã(n)ùêæùëõK(n)-local homotopy categories for varying nùëõn [51]. They denote these Picard groups by ùñØùóÇùñºnsubscriptùñØùóÇùñºùëõ\mathsf{Pic}_{n}. Note that the relevant symmetric monoidal product for fixed nùëõn is

X‚äóY=LK‚Äã(n)‚Äã(X‚àßY)tensor-productùëãùëåsubscriptùêøùêæùëõùëãùëåX\otimes Y=L_{K(n)}(X\wedge Y)

for K‚Äã(n)ùêæùëõK(n)-local XùëãX and YùëåY. They determined ùñØùóÇùñº1subscriptùñØùóÇùñº1\mathsf{Pic}_{1} for all primes pùëùp:

Theorem 9.7.

[51, Theorem 3.3, Proposition 2.7]

9.4. Brauer groups of commutative rings

Probably most of you will know the definition of the Brauer group of a field. But as for many features that we want to transfer to the spectral world we need to consider algebraic concepts developed for commutative rings (not fields).

Azumaya started to think about general Brauer groups [10] in the setting of local rings. A general definition of the Brauer group of a commutative ring RùëÖR was given by Auslander and Goldman [8] as Morita equivalence classes of Azumaya algebras. The Brauer group was then globalized to schemes by Grothendieck [43]. He also shows that the Brauer group of the initial ring ‚Ñ§‚Ñ§\mathbb{Z} is trivial; this is a byproduct of his identification of Brauer groups of number rings in [43, III, Proposition (2.4)].

9.5. Brave new Brauer groups

Baker and Lazarev define in [11] what an Azumaya algebra spectrum is. We use one version of this definition in [15] to develop Brauer groups for commutative ring spectra. Related concepts can be found in [57] and [121].

Fix a cofibrant commutative ring spectrum RùëÖR.

Definition 9.8.

A cofibrant associative RùëÖR-algebra Aùê¥A is called an Azumaya RùëÖR-algebra spectrum if Aùê¥A is dualizable and faithful as an RùëÖR-module spectrum and if the canonical map

A‚àßRAo‚ÜíFR‚Äã(A,A)‚ÜísubscriptùëÖùê¥superscriptùê¥ùëúsubscriptùêπùëÖùê¥ùê¥A\wedge_{R}A^{o}\rightarrow F_{R}(A,A)

is a weak equivalence.

We list some crucial properties of Azumaya algebra spectra. For the first property recall the discussion of derived centers from Definition 6.10.

Proposition 9.9.
  2. (a)

    [11, Proposition 2.3] If Aùê¥A is an Azumaya RùëÖR-algebra spectrum, then Aùê¥A is homotopically central over RùëÖR, i.e., R‚Üíùñ≥ùñßùñßR‚Äã(A)‚ÜíùëÖsubscriptùñ≥ùñßùñßùëÖùê¥R\rightarrow\mathsf{THH}_{R}(A) is a weak equivalence.

  3. (b)

    [15, Proposition 1.3] Every Azumaya RùëÖR-algebra spectrum Aùê¥A is separable over RùëÖR.

  4. (c)

    [15, Proposition 1.5] If Aùê¥A is Azumaya over RùëÖR and if Cùê∂C is a cofibrant commutative RùëÖR-algebra then A‚àßRCsubscriptùëÖùê¥ùê∂A\wedge_{R}C is Azumaya over Cùê∂C. Conversely, if Cùê∂C is as above and dualizable and faithful as an RùëÖR-module, then A‚àßRCsubscriptùëÖùê¥ùê∂A\wedge_{R}C being Azumaya over Cùê∂C implies that Aùê¥A is Azumaya over RùëÖR.

    If Aùê¥A and BùêµB are Azumaya over RùëÖR, then A‚àßRBsubscriptùëÖùê¥ùêµA\wedge_{R}B is also Azumaya over RùëÖR.

  5. (d)

    [15, 2.2] If MùëÄM is a faithful, dualizable, cofibrant RùëÖR‚Äìmodule, then (a cofibrant replacement of) FR‚Äã(M,M)subscriptùêπùëÖùëÄùëÄF_{R}(M,M) is an RùëÖR-Azumaya algebra spectrum.

Thus the endomorphism Azumaya algebras are the ones that are always there and you want to ignore them.

Definition 9.10.

Let Aùê¥A and BùêµB be two Azumaya RùëÖR-algebra spectra. We call them Brauer equivalent if there are dualizable, faithful RùëÖR-modules NùëÅN and MùëÄM such that there is an RùëÖR-algebra equivalence

A‚àßRFR‚Äã(M,M)‚âÉB‚àßRFR‚Äã(N,N).similar-to-or-equalssubscriptùëÖùê¥subscriptùêπùëÖùëÄùëÄsubscriptùëÖùêµsubscriptùêπùëÖùëÅùëÅA\wedge_{R}F_{R}(M,M)\simeq B\wedge_{R}F_{R}(N,N).

We denote by B‚Äãr‚Äã(R)ùêµùëüùëÖBr(R) the set of Brauer equivalence classes of RùëÖR-Azumaya algebra spectra.

Note that B‚Äãr‚Äã(R)ùêµùëüùëÖBr(R) is an abelian group with multiplication induced by the smash product over RùëÖR. Johnson shows [57, Lemma 5.7] that one can reduce the above relation to what he calls Eilenberg-Watts equivalence. This implies that one can still think about the Brauer group of a commutative ring spectrum as the Morita equivalence classes of Azumaya algebra spectra.

We showed a Galois descent result [15, Proposition 3.2], saying that under some natural condition you can descent an Azumaya algebra Cùê∂C over BùêµB to an Azumaya algebra Ch‚ÄãGsuperscriptùê∂‚Ñéùê∫C^{hG} over Aùê¥A is A‚ÜíB‚Üíùê¥ùêµA\rightarrow B is a faithful Gùê∫G-Galois extension with finite Galois group Gùê∫G.

9.6. Examples of Brauer groups

As we know that B‚Äãr‚Äã(‚Ñ§)=0ùêµùëü‚Ñ§0Br(\mathbb{Z})=0, we conjecture [15] that the Brauer group of the initial ring spectrum is also trivial. This conjecture was proven in [6, Corollary 7.17]. They actually showed a much stronger result:

Theorem 9.11.

[6, Theorem 7.16] ‚Äâ If RùëÖR is a connective commutative ring spectrum such that œÄ0‚Äã(R)subscriptùúã0ùëÖ\pi_{0}(R) is either ‚Ñ§‚Ñ§\mathbb{Z} or the Witt vectors W‚Äã(ùîΩq)ùëäsubscriptùîΩùëûW(\mathbb{F}_{q}), then the Brauer group of RùëÖR is trivial.

Different approaches can be used to construct a Brauer space for a commutative ring spectrum RùëÖR, B‚ÄãrRùêµsubscriptùëüùëÖBr_{R}, [6, Definition 7.1], [36, ¬ß5], [119] and to show that this space is a delooping of the Picard space, ùñØùñ®ùñ¢ùñØùñ®ùñ¢\mathsf{PIC}

Œ©‚ÄãB‚ÄãrR‚âÉùñØùñ®ùñ¢‚Äã(R)similar-to-or-equalsŒ©ùêµsubscriptùëüùëÖùñØùñ®ùñ¢ùëÖ\Omega Br_{R}\simeq\mathsf{PIC}(R)

with œÄ0‚Äã(B‚ÄãrR)‚âÖB‚Äãr‚Äã(R)subscriptùúã0ùêµsubscriptùëüùëÖùêµùëüùëÖ\pi_{0}(Br_{R})\cong Br(R).

An important question in the classical context of Brauer groups of schemes is to which extend these groups can be controlled by the second √©tale cohomology group. See the introduction of [121] for a nice overview. To√´n shows that for quasi-compact and quasi-separated schemes XùëãX one can identify the derived Brauer group of XùëãX with H√©t1‚Äã(X;ùîæm)√óH√©t2‚Äã(X;ùîæm)subscriptsuperscriptùêª1√©tùëãsubscriptùîæùëösubscriptsuperscriptùêª2√©tùëãsubscriptùîæùëöH^{1}_{\text{\'{e}t}}(X;\mathbb{G}_{m})\times H^{2}_{\text{\'{e}t}}(X;\mathbb{G}_{m}). The work of Antieau and Gepner [6, ¬ß7.4] relates Brauer groups of connective commutative ring spectra to √©tale cohomology groups by establishing a spectral sequence starting from √©tale cohomology groups for √©tale sheaves over a connective commutative ring spectrum converging to the homotopy groups of the Brauer space [6, Theorem 7.12].

It is not hard to see that the integral version of the quaternions gives a non-trivial element in B‚Äãr‚Äã(S‚Äã[12])ùêµùëüùëÜdelimited-[]12Br(S[\frac{1}{2}]) [15, Proposition 6.3]; Antieau and Gepner show [6, Corollary 7.18]

B‚Äãr‚Äã(S‚Äã[1p])‚âÖ‚Ñ§/2‚Äã‚Ñ§¬†for all primes¬†‚ÄãpùêµùëüùëÜdelimited-[]1ùëù‚Ñ§2‚Ñ§¬†for all primes¬†ùëùBr(S\textstyle{[\frac{1}{p}]})\cong\mathbb{Z}/2\mathbb{Z}\quad\text{ for all primes }p

and they prove the existence of a short exact sequence

0‚ÜíB‚Äãr‚Äã(S(p))‚Üí‚Ñ§/2‚Äã‚Ñ§‚äï‚®Åq‚â†p‚Ñö/‚Ñ§‚Üí‚Ñö/‚Ñ§‚Üí0‚Üí0ùêµùëüsubscriptùëÜùëù‚Üídirect-sum‚Ñ§2‚Ñ§subscriptdirect-sumùëûùëù‚Ñö‚Ñ§‚Üí‚Ñö‚Ñ§‚Üí00\rightarrow Br(S_{(p)})\rightarrow\mathbb{Z}/2\mathbb{Z}\oplus\bigoplus_{q\neq p}\mathbb{Q}/\mathbb{Z}\rightarrow\mathbb{Q}/\mathbb{Z}\rightarrow 0

by applying [6, Corollary 7.13] where they calculate the homotopy groups of the Brauer space of any connective commutative ring spectrum RùëÖR in terms of √©tale cohomology groups and the homotopy groups of RùëÖR.

They use the classical exact sequence for the Brauer group of the rationals [43, ¬ß2] coming from the Albert-Brauer-Hasse-Noether theorem:

0‚ÜíB‚Äãr‚Äã(‚Ñö)‚Üí‚Ñ§/2‚Äã‚Ñ§‚äï‚®Åp‚Äã¬†prime¬†B‚Äãr‚Äã(‚Ñöp)‚Üí‚Ñö/‚Ñ§‚Üí0‚Üí0ùêµùëü‚Ñö‚Üídirect-sum‚Ñ§2‚Ñ§subscriptdirect-sumùëù¬†prime¬†ùêµùëüsubscript‚Ñöùëù‚Üí‚Ñö‚Ñ§‚Üí00\rightarrow Br(\mathbb{Q})\rightarrow\mathbb{Z}/2\mathbb{Z}\oplus\bigoplus_{p\text{ prime }}Br(\mathbb{Q}_{p})\rightarrow\mathbb{Q}/\mathbb{Z}\rightarrow 0

with B‚Äãr‚Äã(‚Ñöp)=‚Ñö/‚Ñ§ùêµùëüsubscript‚Ñöùëù‚Ñö‚Ñ§Br(\mathbb{Q}_{p})=\mathbb{Q}/\mathbb{Z}. This determines B‚Äãr‚Äã(‚Ñ§‚Äã[1p])ùêµùëü‚Ñ§delimited-[]1ùëùBr(\mathbb{Z}[\frac{1}{p}]) and B‚Äãr‚Äã(‚Ñ§(p))ùêµùëüsubscript‚Ñ§ùëùBr(\mathbb{Z}_{(p)}) and this in turn gives the above result for the sphere spectra with pùëùp inverted or localized at pùëùp.

In [15, Theorem 10.1] we show that the K‚Äã(n)ùêæùëõK(n)-local Brauer group of the K‚Äã(n)ùêæùëõK(n)-local sphere is non-trivial at least for odd primes and n>1ùëõ1n>1.

Gepner and Lawson prove a version of Galois descent for a suitable ‚àû\infty-category of Azumaya algebras:

Theorem 9.12.

[36, Theorem 6.15] ‚Äâ There is an equivalence of symmetric monoidal ‚àû\infty-categories

A‚ÄãzA‚Üí(A‚ÄãzB)h‚ÄãG‚Üíùê¥subscriptùëßùê¥superscriptùê¥subscriptùëßùêµ‚Ñéùê∫Az_{A}\rightarrow(Az_{B})^{hG}

for every Gùê∫G-Galois extension A‚ÜíB‚Üíùê¥ùêµA\rightarrow B with finite Gùê∫G.

They also construct a map of ‚àû\infty-groupoids A‚ÄãzR‚ÜíB‚ÄãrR‚Üíùê¥subscriptùëßùëÖùêµsubscriptùëüùëÖAz_{R}\rightarrow Br_{R} for any commutative ring spectrum RùëÖR and show that this map is essentially surjective, such that equality in œÄ0‚Äã(B‚ÄãrR)subscriptùúã0ùêµsubscriptùëüùëÖ\pi_{0}(Br_{R}) corresponds precisely to Morita equivalence. They investigate the algebraic Brauer groups (i.e., the Morita classes of Azumaya algebras over the coefficients) [36, ¬ß7.1] of 222-periodic commutative ring spectra with vanishing odd homotopy groups, such as ùêæùëàùêæùëà\mathit{KU} or Ensubscriptùê∏ùëõE_{n}, by relating them to the classical Brauer-Wall group of œÄ0subscriptùúã0\pi_{0} of the ring spectrum and they identify a non-trivial Morita class of a quaternion ùêæùëÇùêæùëÇ\mathit{KO}-algebra that becomes Morita-trivial over ùêæùëàùêæùëà\mathit{KU}.

There is recent work by Hopkins and Lurie [50] who identify the K‚Äã(n)ùêæùëõK(n)-local Brauer group of a Lubin-Tate spectrum Eùê∏E at all primes. For odd primes they obtain:

Theorem 9.13.

[50, Theorem 1.0.11] ‚Äâ The K‚Äã(n)ùêæùëõK(n)-local Brauer group of Eùê∏E is the product of the Brauer-Wall group of the residue field œÄ0‚Äã(E)/msubscriptùúã0ùê∏ùëö\pi_{0}(E)/m and a group B‚Äãr‚Ä≤‚Äã(E)ùêµsuperscriptùëü‚Ä≤ùê∏Br^{\prime}(E) which in turn can be expressed as an inverse limit of abelian groups B‚Äãr‚Ñì‚Ä≤ùêµsubscriptsuperscriptùëü‚Ä≤‚ÑìBr^{\prime}_{\ell} such that the kernel of B‚Äãr‚Ñì‚Ä≤‚ÜíB‚Äãr‚Ñì‚àí1‚Ä≤‚Üíùêµsubscriptsuperscriptùëü‚Ä≤‚Ñìùêµsubscriptsuperscriptùëü‚Ä≤‚Ñì1Br^{\prime}_{\ell}\rightarrow Br^{\prime}_{\ell-1} is non-canonically isomorphic to m‚Ñì+2/m‚Ñì+3superscriptùëö‚Ñì2superscriptùëö‚Ñì3m^{\ell+2}/m^{\ell+3}.

One ingredient is their construction of atomic Eùê∏E-algebra spectra [50, Definition 1.0.2] via a Thom spectrum construction relative to Eùê∏E for polarizations of lattices [50, Definition 3.2.1] using the machinery from [1, 2]. Here, the starting point is a lattice ŒõŒõ\Lambda of finite rank together with a polarization map Q:K‚Äã(Œõ,1)‚ÜíùñØùñ®ùñ¢‚Äã(E)‚âÉùñØùóÇùñº‚Äã(E)√óB‚ÄãG‚ÄãL1‚Äã(E):ùëÑ‚ÜíùêæŒõ1ùñØùñ®ùñ¢ùê∏similar-to-or-equalsùñØùóÇùñºùê∏ùêµùê∫subscriptùêø1ùê∏Q\colon K(\Lambda,1)\rightarrow\mathsf{PIC}(E)\simeq\mathsf{Pic}(E)\times BGL_{1}(E).
